<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel checks carried out in 2005 on the administration of value added tax between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted material informs about the progress and results of the parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší kontrolní úradom Slovenskej republiky, which focused on the area of value added tax administration and the use of the information system VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so the revenue from value added tax affects not only the national budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">The parallel control actions were mainly aimed at checking the procedure of tax authorities in examining the amount of value added tax paid in commercial transactions between individual Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of VIES has enabled the electronic exchange of information on the registration of VAT payers in individual Member States of the European Union and on the commercial transactions carried out by them.</seg>
<seg id="7">The discrepancy between the VIES data and the data in the VAT return submitted by the taxpayer should alert the tax authorities to suspicious cases and allow the detection of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefit of the parallel checks carried out was not only the exchange of information on the procedure of the tax or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but in particular the examination of the use of the VIES system in the control of the application of the right to exemption from value added tax in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The lessons learned from the implementation of parallel controls will contribute to the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of further parallel controls in cooperation with the control institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel checks on the administration of value added tax for the period 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (CZ) 05 / 19 (SK) 22 / 2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration, (SK) Control of the procedure of the tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and the performance of VIES tasks for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "SAO, Czech Republic") and the Najvyššší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky (hereinafter referred to as "SAO SR") concluded a contract on cooperation in audit activities on 12 September 2005.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in the implementation of the parallel audit actions "Administration of Value Added Tax," included in the plan of audit activities of the SAO, the Czech Republic for 2005 under No 05 / 19 and "Control of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of taxes on added value and fulfilment of tasks within the VIES system on the list of informants among the member landscapes of the EÚ," included in the plan of audit activities of the SAO SR under No 22 / 2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">The control actions carried out in parallel were in the nature of coordinated control.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated control was processed within the meaning of the European Enforcement Regulation No 31 for the INTOSAI control standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information to the extent provided for by the contract concluded and the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated inspection was to verify selected cases of supplies and acquisitions of goods in suspicious commercial transactions between value added tax payers from the Czech Republic ("the Czech Republic") and the Slovak Republic ("the Slovak Republic").</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties have contractually agreed to provide each other with information from public sources, from the electronic system VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) and data on received and sent requests for the examination of business transactions between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">On the territory of the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by the State Budget Department and the regional unions of Central Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited entities were the Ministry of Finance and 12 tax offices: The tax office in Mladá Boleslav, the tax office in Cologne, the tax office in Teplice, the tax office in Karlovy Vary, the tax office in Tábor, the tax office in Brno III, the tax office in Znojmo, the tax office in Zlín, the tax office in Šumperk, the tax office in Ostrava I, the tax office for Prague 7 and the tax office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic was carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the Slovak SAO in cooperation with the expositions of the Slovak SAO Banská Bystrica and Košice at 9 selected tax offices: The Bratislava I Tax Office, the Komárno Tax Office, the Trenčín Tax Office, the Prievidza Tax Office, the Zvolen Tax Office, the Dolný Kubín Tax Office, the Košice II Tax Office, the Košice V Tax Office and Michalovce Tax Office.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of the checks:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel control actions was to examine the procedure of the tax and tax authorities in the administration of value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") following the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as "the EU") and to examine the use of the VIES electronic information system, in particular when checking the application of the VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="27">The audited period of coordinated control was from 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions An electronic VIES system is in place in EU Member States that allows tax authorities to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt the taxable transaction from VAT and allows the country of destination to check whether the acquirer has correctly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="29">The VIES system is not centralised within the EU; each Member State develops its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit found differences between the national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">Recapitulative statements show the value of supplies of goods to other EU Member States, and the value of services provided is not included in recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from recapitulative statements submitted by Czech payers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of the tax authorities, where they are compared with data on supplies of goods to other EU Member States included in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The tax authorities transmit the data from the recapitulative statements to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In the Slovak Republic, data from summary reports submitted by Slovak taxpayers at tax offices are only converted into electronic form and processed centrally at the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers report the value of supplies of goods and the value of supplies of services to other EU Member States on separate lines of VAT returns, which makes it possible to compare the values reported in the recapitulative statements with the values of supplies of goods according to VAT returns and to identify any differences between them.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the Slovak Republic, the values of goods and services supplied to other EU Member States are reported cumulatively on the common line of VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, in the Slovak Republic, the system does not allow the automatic identification of differences between the values of supplies of goods according to VAT returns and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the value of supplies of goods in VAT returns makes it possible to use the results of data comparisons to check the VAT exemption for supplies of goods to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="39">The data received from recapitulative statements submitted by payers in other EU Member States are processed into CLOs and compared with the value of the acquisition of goods stated by payers from the Czech Republic and Slovakia respectively in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the Slovak Republic, these data are sent to the tax authorities and the tax authorities themselves decide which cases of differences to examine.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) will determine which quantified differences between the values of supplies and acquisitions of goods must be examined by the tax authorities and will send a list of these cases to the local tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that, for the most significant variations, it will be examined whether the VAT on the acquisition of goods has been declared at the correct level.</seg>
<seg id="43">The audit also highlighted some problems in the VAT administration system due to the complications caused by the different reporting of intra-community transactions (i.e. supplies and acquisitions of goods made by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Recapitulative statements are made in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum time limit for processing and sending data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">Shortening the reporting period to one month, together with shortening the processing period, would allow earlier access to VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="46">This would allow tax authorities to check more effectively whether VAT on intra-Community purchases has been declared at the correct level.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, the submission of VAT returns and recapitulative statements for the same tax year (month) would allow faster verification of whether the payer has declared identical values of supplies of goods to the EU in both the recapitulative statement and the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="48">The differences between the values of delivery of goods reported by EU payers and the values of acquisition of goods reported by Czech and Slovak payers were due, among other things, to the different reporting of data on intra-community delivery and acquisition in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These included, for example, the inclusion of received advances in recapitulative statements, or the reporting of intra-community supplies in the supplier's recapitulative statement in a quarter other than intra-community acquisitions in the customer's VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="50">Harmonising the conditions for the reporting of these data within the EU would make the control activities of Member States' tax administrations more efficient.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic was also focused on the examination of selected intra-community transactions between the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">Together, a total of 40 cases of commercial transactions between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined, where there were doubts about their implementation or suspicions of VAT evasion.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of Slovakia found, among other things, the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="54">Tax entities have declared in their VAT returns, for the purpose of improperly obtaining an excess VAT deduction, the carrying out of intra-Community transactions which have not actually taken place;</seg>
<seg id="55">Tax entities reported intra-community supplies in carousel transactions where there was a deliberate multiple reduction in the value of supplies in order to draw excess VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">In their VAT returns and recapitulative statements, suppliers declared intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to purchasers who were so-called "lost companies" and did not declare the tax on the goods acquired;</seg>
<seg id="57">The suppliers made intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to tax entities not registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In such cases, the supply should not have been exempt from VAT and should have been subject to tax in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">Suppliers declared intra-Community supplies in their VAT returns at a higher value than those declared by purchasers of intra-Community acquisitions, in some cases where VAT was declared at an incorrect level.</seg>
<seg id="60">The findings of the audit exercise showed that VIES provides tax authorities with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">Tax administrations should pay particular attention to the rigorous examination of differences between data reported by VAT payers and data in the VIES system and the use of all information in tax procedures.</seg>
<seg id="62">The issue of value added tax after the accession of the Czech Republic and Slovakia to the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On 1 May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">After joining the EU, internal borders and border controls on the movement of goods within the EU have been abolished.</seg>
<seg id="66">Until 30 April 2004, the tax authority was the competent tax authority, with the exception of the import of goods and occasional bus services in the country, where the tax authority was the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="67">In connection with the adoption of the new Act No. 235 / 2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter "Act No. 235 / 2004 Coll.") and Act No. 222 / 2004 Z. z., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter "Act No. 222 / 2004 Z. z."), the administration of VAT on the acquisition of goods and services (previously imports) from other EU Member States passed from the customs authorities to the tax and tax authorities respectively.</seg>
<seg id="68">The supply of goods in the Czech Republic under the provisions of Section 13 of Act No 235 / 2004 Coll. means the transfer of the right to dispose of goods as owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">The supply of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU Member State is the supply of goods that have actually been dispatched or transported to another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="70">Under the provisions of Section 64 of Act No 235 / 2004 Coll. it is an exempt taxable transaction with the right to deduct VAT if the goods are delivered to a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">In the Slovak Republic, according to the provisions of Section 8 of Act No 222 / 2004 Z. Z., the supply of tangible property in which the right of ownership is changed is considered to be a supply of goods.</seg>
<seg id="72">The transfer of goods owned by a taxable person from the territory of the country to another Member State shall also be regarded as a supply of goods where those goods are dispatched or transported by that person or on his behalf to another Member State for the purposes of his business.</seg>
<seg id="73">Under Section 43 of Act No 222 / 2004 Z. z., the supply of goods from the country to another Member State is exempt from VAT if the person acquiring the goods is a person identified for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="74">The acquisition of goods from another EU Member State in the Czech Republic under the provisions of Section 16 of Act No 235 / 2004 Coll. means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of goods which are dispatched or transported to the purchaser by a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Czech payer purchases goods at a price excluding VAT and is obliged to declare VAT in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of Section 25 of Act No. 235 / 2004 Coll., if the conditions set out in the provisions of Section 73 of this Act are met, he will be entitled to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="76">The acquisition of goods in the Czech Republic from another EU Member State in the Slovak Republic under the provisions of Section 11 of Act No 222 / 2004 Z. z. means the acquisition of the right to dispose, as owner, of movable tangible property dispatched or transported to the customer by or on behalf of the supplier or the customer to the Czech Republic from another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">Tax liability in the Slovak Republic arises when the payer acquires goods in the Czech Republic from another Member State according to the provisions of Section 20 of Act No 222 / 2004 Z.Z.</seg>
<seg id="78">The payer can deduct VAT under the provisions of Section 49 of Act No 222 / 2004 Z. Z. if the tax is charged by him on the acquisition of goods in the country from another Member State under the provisions of Sections 11 and 11a of this Act.</seg>
<seg id="79">According to the provisions of Section 17 of Act No 235 / 2004 Coll., or Section 45 of Act No 222 / 2004 Z. z., trilateral trade is a trade concluded between three persons registered for VAT in three different EU Member States, where the object of the trade is the supply of the same goods between the three persons.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intra-community transactions are supplies and acquisitions of goods between VAT payers from different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="81">The total volumes of intra-community transactions between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic are shown in the table below.</seg>
<seg id="82">Vies system</seg>
<seg id="83">A VAT information exchange system has been set up within the EU to monitor the application of VAT exemptions for intra-Community supplies of goods.</seg>
<seg id="84">It includes the VIES electronic system, which allows EU tax authorities to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt the taxable transaction from VAT and vice versa, whether the acquirer duly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="85">The VIES information system is not centralised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="86">Each Member State develops its own VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="87">National systems operate on a common principle and are interconnected through a common EU communication network, the CCN (Common Communication Network; see diagram below).</seg>
<seg id="88">In the Czech Republic, the VIES system was connected to an automated tax information system ("ADIS"), in the Slovak Republic to the application software of the tax information system ("APV DIS").</seg>
<seg id="89">These systems are used by the tax and tax authorities as technical support for executive and management activities in the administration of taxes and fees.</seg>
<seg id="90">International administrative cooperation</seg>
<seg id="91">Through international administrative cooperation, the tax administration of each EU Member State obtains information on tax entities that it would not have been able to obtain on its own without such cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="92">The main objective of international administrative cooperation is the fight against tax evasion and losses.</seg>
<seg id="93">Under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003, each Member State establishes, within the internal organisational structure, a central unit in the field of administrative cooperation between EU Member States in the management of VAT, known as the Central Liaison Office (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="94">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance - the Central Financial and Tax Directorate, where the Department of International Cooperation in the Administration of VAT (hereinafter referred to as "MF CLO") has been established, performs tasks arising from international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="95">The function of CLO in the Slovak Republic is performed by the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic, the Department of International Administrative Cooperation ("DR CLO").</seg>
<seg id="96">These departments communicate with EU foreign administrations mainly in the field of VIES information exchange, spontaneous information and information exchange at the request of EU tax administrations, coordination of multilateral (simultaneous) tax controls, verification of tax identification numbers (TIN) of persons registered for VAT in other EU Member States, and communicate with the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="97">In order to examine a particular intra-Community transaction or to obtain further information relating to a particular tax entity, the tax and tax authorities send requests for information to the EU via MF CLO and DR CLO respectively.</seg>
<seg id="98">Through these requests, they obtain information from the requested Member States which they can use to correctly determine VAT.</seg>
<seg id="99">Requests for information between EU Member States' CLOs are mostly sent in electronic form, using a standardised SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="100">Selected control findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="101">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic focused mainly on the examination of selected intra-community transactions carried out between the two states and on the level of use of information obtained in the form of international cooperation by the financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="102">In 30 cases, the SAO, the Czech Republic requested the SAO to examine business transactions between 19 Czech and 25 Slovak tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="103">The SAO asked the SAO, the Czech Republic to examine in 10 cases business transactions carried out between 7 Slovak and 10 Czech tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="104">An examination of intra-community transactions revealed, among other things:</seg>
<seg id="105">O</seg>
<seg id="106">The SAO, the Czech Republic asked the SAO of the Slovak Republic to examine the procedure of the tax administration, to which a reply to a request for information was sent.</seg>
<seg id="107">The Slovak Tax Office, using the SCAC form, requested verification of the supply of goods (footwear) in the third quarter of 2004 from a Slovak payer in the value of 2 847,000 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="108">The tax office in the Czech Republic replied that the Czech payer only stated the purchase of goods with this value in an additional VAT return and delivered the same goods back to Slovak tax entities with a value of CZK 2,550,000 by the end of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="109">On the basis of the international cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR, it was found that the locally competent tax office fully recognised the Slovak supplier's right to an excess deduction of VAT arising from, among other things, this supply.</seg>
<seg id="110">This tax office did not provide information on the suspicion of re-export to the tax authorities of the locally relevant customers of goods imported back from the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="111">This will provide an incentive for further investigation of business activities in relation to possible carousel fraud.</seg>
<seg id="112">O</seg>
<seg id="113">The Czech tax authority asked through the SCAC form for verification of the delivery of a technology line to SR worth CZK 4,850,000 in the second quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="114">The tax procedure carried out in SR showed that only part of the technology line was delivered, and components worth CZK 3,395,000 were not delivered.</seg>
<seg id="115">In examining this case, the SAO SR found that the VAT on the taxable transaction carried out was declared by the Slovak tax entity on the amount of CZK 4,850,000 in the VAT return ("DAP") for the tax year 7 / 2004.</seg>
<seg id="116">The SAO, Czech Republic also found that the Czech payer reported an excess VAT deduction of CZK 655,000 in his DAP for that quarter, which was due to the application of a VAT deduction on the purchase of this technology line from another domestic payer.</seg>
<seg id="117">On the basis of the results of the investigation, the Czech tax office concluded that the Czech and Slovak tax entities created a business relationship for the purpose of illegally obtaining an excess VAT deduction, questioned the performance of the taxable transaction and did not recognise the Czech payer's part of the right to deduct the tax in the amount of CZK 647,000.</seg>
<seg id="118">O</seg>
<seg id="119">In 2004, the Slovak tax authority asked through the SCAC form for verification of the supply of goods (copying machines) to the Czech payer in the value of 24,246,000 Sk made in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="120">In November 2002, the Slovak payer bought these goods from another tax entity in Slovakia, worth 29,667,000 Sk, and then sold them to a Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Slovak tax entity has claimed an excess VAT deduction for the relevant tax year.</seg>
<seg id="122">In a tax investigation carried out in the Czech Republic, it was found that the Czech tax entity did not cooperate with the tax administration and did not file a DAP for the fourth quarter of 2002 or the following period.</seg>
<seg id="123">The SAO SR found that on the basis of the result of the tax audit, the Slovak tax administration did not recognise the right to an excess deduction of 5,541,000 Sk applied in the DAP for the month of 11 / 2002 and established the tax liability of 1,750,000 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="124">At the same time, that taxpayer was not granted an exemption from VAT in respect of the export of goods in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="125">O</seg>
<seg id="126">The Czech tax authority received an order from MF CLO to verify the value of the acquired goods for the third quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="127">According to data from VIES, the Czech payer was to purchase goods (diluent) worth CZK 3,767,000 from Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="128">This tax entity did not cooperate with the tax authority, it did not file a DAP and the VAT for the months 7 to 12 / 2004 was assessed ex officio in the amount of CZK 0.</seg>
<seg id="129">The Czech tax authority asked through the SCAC form to check whether deliveries of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic took place, in what quantity and price (according to invoices).</seg>
<seg id="130">In reply, the Slovak local tax office sent a copy of the invoice, the consignment notes and a request for payment of the invoice.</seg>
<seg id="131">The SAO SR found that the Slovak payer had been granted an exemption with the right to deduct VAT on this supply.</seg>
<seg id="132">The SAO, Czech Republic found that the Czech tax authority assessed the response to the request for information received from the Slovak Republic as evidence showing that the company had purchased goods from another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="133">On the basis of further investigation, the tax office in the Czech Republic will ask the superior authority for a review of the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="134">O</seg>
<seg id="135">The Slovak company supplied goods (particle board products) to, among others, an American company, which stored these goods in the Czech Republic in a free zone.</seg>
<seg id="136">The operator of this free zone was identified on the invoices as the consignee of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="137">In 2004, for example, an American company purchased $57,600 worth of particle board from a Slovak payer (at a unit price of $100 per piece), which it placed in a free zone.</seg>
<seg id="138">Subsequently, the company transferred ownership of the goods to a Swiss company, worth USD 14,400 (unit price of USD 25 / piece), and the goods were exported back to SR.</seg>
<seg id="139">The goods were not unloaded in the Czech Republic but left the area of the free zone on the same means of transport.</seg>
<seg id="140">The Slovak tax authority initiated tax inspections of individual tax years 2004 and 2005 at the supplier of goods on suspicion of carousel transactions.</seg>
<seg id="141">The verification of the underlying transactions was requested from the Czech local tax authorities through several SCAC forms.</seg>
<seg id="142">The individual responses gradually created a picture of the shops and confirmed the involvement of stakeholders from the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in the carousel shops.</seg>
<seg id="143">The SAO, the Czech Republic, in cooperation with the SAO SR, found that in these business relations, there was a deliberate multiple decrease in the value of goods.</seg>
<seg id="144">On the basis of the information gathered, the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic concluded that in this case of the carousel trade it is free price formation (i.e. the import of undervalued goods and their overvaluation by domestic companies located in the chain between the importer and the exporter), which is not a violation of the VAT Act in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="145">Under current legislation, the payment of excess VAT to export companies cannot be prevented as they meet all the conditions of the law to exempt supplies from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="146">O</seg>
<seg id="147">The Czech payer's VAT registration was cancelled on 12 July 2005.</seg>
<seg id="148">On 27 October 2005, following a voluntary application for VAT registration, the company became a tax payer again.</seg>
<seg id="149">For the month of 8 / 2005 (i.e. the period when he was not a VAT payer), the Czech tax entity entered into the DAP the value of the purchase of goods (printing press) from the Slovak Republic in the amount of CZK 1,174,000 and claimed the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="150">This value corresponded to a supply of goods from a Slovak payer in the amount of 1,530,000 Sk, which the Slovak payer stated in the DAP as a supply of goods to another EU Member State with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="151">The Slovak tax authority requested to verify the said supply using the SCAC form because the Slovak supplier did not prove how he acquired the goods delivered to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO, Czech Republic found that the Czech payer does not cooperate with the tax authority and does not reside at the address listed in the Commercial Register.</seg>
<seg id="153">As part of the international exchange of information, a local investigation will be carried out in the Czech Republic by the locally competent tax authority in order to verify the data.</seg>
<seg id="154">O</seg>
<seg id="155">The Slovak payer included in the summary report for the third quarter of 2004 the delivery of goods worth 956,000 Sk to a tax entity from the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="156">The VAT number of the Czech entity was marked as incorrect by the VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="157">Verification in the database of payers revealed that such TIN was never allocated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="158">According to the invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was the execution of electrical assembly work on real estate in the Czech Republic, not the delivery of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, but the provision of services.</seg>
<seg id="159">The services were invoiced without VAT, as the Czech entity informed the Slovak entity that it was registered as a VAT payer in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="160">The Slovak tax authority requested to verify these facts by means of the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="161">The SAO, the Czech Republic, by asking the local tax authority in the Czech Republic, found that the tax entity listed on invoices as a customer was never registered as a VAT payer in the Czech Republic, did not declare the tax on received services from the Slovak entity and did not declare the tax on the acquisition of goods.</seg>
<seg id="162">Neither the local investigation nor the tax audit was carried out on the Czech entity, its current residence is unknown.</seg>
<seg id="163">On the basis of an international exchange of information, the Czech tax authorities learned that the Czech tax entity had become a VAT payer by law by accepting the service.</seg>
<seg id="164">The Slovak tax entity will be subject to a tax audit for the first to fourth quarters of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="165">O</seg>
<seg id="166">In the summary report for the third quarter of 2004, the Slovak payer declared the delivery of goods worth 1,055,000 Sk to the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="167">According to invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was the execution of electrical assembly works on real estate in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="168">It was not a supply of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, but a supply of services.</seg>
<seg id="169">The Slovak tax authority requested to verify these facts by means of the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="170">The SAO, the Czech Republic, by asking the local tax authority in the Czech Republic, found that the Czech entity was a VAT payer at the time of the delivery and a local investigation was carried out to examine the acquisition of goods from other EU Member States in the third quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="171">On the basis of this local investigation, it was found that the present case was not really about the acquisition of goods, but about the acquisition of services, which the Czech entity also reported in the regular DAP.</seg>
<seg id="172">The tax office also found that the Czech entity did not pay the correct amount of VAT for the tax year of the third quarter of 2004 as a result of a bad procedure in the calculation of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="173">The taxpayer submits an additional DAP.</seg>
<seg id="174">The SAO SR, when questioned by the local tax office, found that the Slovak payer had erroneously stated the provision of the service in a summary report and would be subject to a tax audit for the 1st to 4th quarters of 2004.</seg>
