<seg id="287">The SAO, Czech Republic found that in 33 cases the audited tax authorities did not check the irregularities in the values of the intra-Community acquisitions referred to in the verification orders received.</seg>
<seg id="288">In these cases, the total difference between the values stated in the SH of payers from other EU Member States and the DAP of Czech payers was at least CZK 148,319,000.</seg>
<seg id="289">The SAO, Czech Republic selected 533 files of tax entities for inspection, for which the audited tax authorities received a verification order from the Ministry of Finance.</seg>
<seg id="290">The inspection found the following most common causes of differences between the values stated in the DAP of the customer and in the SH of the supplier: On the part of the customer (Czech payer) in 263 cases the customer did not declare the acquisition of goods in the regular DAP, in 93 cases the payer admitted the acquisition of goods in a different tax period than in which he was obliged to declare the tax, in 6 cases the customer stated the value of the purchased goods in the wrong DAP line, on the part of the supplier (EU payer) in 88 cases the EU payers included in their SH the values of the services provided to the Czech payer, of which 54 were Slovak payers, in 39 cases the suppliers included in the SH the supply of goods in a different tax period than the Czech purchasers in their DAP, in 22 cases the suppliers stated in the SH the incorrect VAT number of the Czech payer, in 16 cases the suppliers stated in the SH the incorrect values of the supply of goods, in 12 cases the suppliers included in the SH the value of goods delivered to the Czech Republic before 1 May 2004, in 5 cases the suppliers included in the SH the value of the advances received.</seg>
<seg id="291">On the part of Slovak payers, the value of the services provided was most often erroneously included in the SH.</seg>
