<seg id="352">5.2 International exchange of information level L3</seg>
<seg id="353">The exchange of information at L3 level is initiated by locally competent tax authorities, who send their requests for information (hereinafter referred to as "JOI") or spontaneous information (hereinafter referred to as "SPI") relating to a particular tax entity or transaction through MF CLO, respectively.</seg>
<seg id="354">Dr CLO to another EU Member State. The aim of ŽOI is, for example, to prove the execution of a given transaction in the context of intra-community transactions, to check a certain VAT number, etc.</seg>
<seg id="355">In the case of an SPI, it is a communication of information relevant to tax administrations in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="356">Cooperation in the field of information exchange is governed by Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003.</seg>
<seg id="357">The maximum time limit for replying to an EOI was set at 3 months in Article 8 of this Regulation.</seg>
<seg id="358">The conditions for the admissibility of applications are governed by a decision of the Commission of the European Communities of 15.11.2004, which stipulates that, unless otherwise agreed by the participating States, an EOI must relate to commercial transactions with a value of at least EUR 1 500, excluding VAT.</seg>
<seg id="359">Where an EOI relates to a commercial transaction with a value of less than EUR 15 000 excluding VAT, the requested authority may refuse to respond in view of its workload.</seg>
<seg id="360">The procedure for processing incoming ŽOI by the tax administration of the Czech Republic, including the indication of the internal time limits set for processing at each organisational level, is illustrated in the following diagram.</seg>
<seg id="361">In the Slovak Republic, the deadline for processing ŽOI by the tax authorities was set internally at 2 months in order to comply with the three-month deadline under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003.</seg>
<seg id="362">MF CLO received a total of 29 ŽOI and 3 SPI from Slovakia from 1 May 2004 to 30 June 2005.</seg>
<seg id="363">Of the 29 IOUs received, 26 (89.7%) were discharged within the stipulated time limit of 3 months and 3 (10.3%) were discharged after that time limit.</seg>
<seg id="364">During the same period, DR CLO from the Czech Republic received a total of 71 ŽOI and 7 SPI.</seg>
<seg id="365">Of the 71 received by the JOI, 64 (i.e. 90.1%) were dealt with within the stipulated time limit of 3 months, 5 (i.e. 7.0%) were dealt with after this time limit (for the remaining 2 cases it was not possible to determine the time limit from the submitted material).</seg>
<seg id="366">The following graph contains more detailed data on the processing time of IOUs received by MF CLO and DR CLO, respectively.</seg>
<seg id="367">The reasons given on the SCAC forms for sending a JOI are set out in the table below.</seg>
<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">On the basis of international cooperation, compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT has been examined, as well as the use of VIES to exchange information between EU Member States, in particular when monitoring the exercise of the right to exemption from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation has made it possible to examine selected intra-Community transactions between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="371">An examination of the selected transactions revealed that, based on an international exchange of information, the tax administrations of both countries detected cases of companies carrying out fictitious intra-Community business transactions in order to obtain excess VAT deductions, as well as cases where the purchasers did not declare VAT on the received supplies of goods at the correct level.</seg>
<seg id="372">The audit also revealed differences in the processing and use of VIES data by the tax administrations of the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also highlighted problems caused by the different reporting of data on intra-community supplies and purchases of goods in different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">Harmonising the conditions for the reporting of these data within the EU would make the control activities of Member States' tax administrations more efficient.</seg>
<seg id="375">An examination of the procedure of the tax and tax authorities in the administration of VAT and the use of the VIES system revealed that the tax and tax authorities did not make sufficient use of all the possibilities of the VIES system and the relevant legal powers.</seg>
<seg id="376">In addition, it was found that VIES did not provide up-to-date information on the supply of goods and the validity of the VAT registration of tax entities in all cases.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SAO SR compared the data on the occurrence of erroneous data in the SH, processed before the start of the audit, with data processed after the end of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="378">Comparing these figures, it was clear that the audit of the SAO SR had an impact not only on the reduction of the number of SH with misstated VAT numbers, but also on the reduction of the number of uncorrected errors in SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In the event of irregularities in the reported data, the SAO asked the tax authorities to carry out local investigations or to carry out tax audits.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, the Czech Republic did not have such an option under the current legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The findings of the audit exercise showed that VIES provided tax authorities with the basic information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">As there is still scope for tax evasion in this area, there is a need to pay close attention to intra-community transactions when managing VAT.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was drawn up in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Chairman of the Najvyšššššie Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
