<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the administration of value added tax and excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material gives an overview of the progress and results of the parallel control actions carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Najvyšší kontrolní úradom Sloven-skej republiky, which were focused on the area of value added administration and excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the supreme audit authorities of the two countries was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement on control activities concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel control actions was chosen in view of the fact that indirect taxes make a significant contribution to the revenue of the national budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The design of value added tax, which allows for the refund of excess deductions, provides scope for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High rates of excise duties, especially on tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean high profits for those who escape taxation by illegally selling these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">In view of the need to address this issue comprehensively across the European Union, the VAT Working Group has been set up by the supreme audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union, in which the highest audit offices of both countries are actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the control actions carried out can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but in particular in the joint effort to identify problem areas of indirect tax administration in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The experience and knowledge gained will be used in the framework of the planned indirect tax controls, aimed in particular at involving the tax authorities of both countries in the VIES system, which allows the movement of goods between the Member States of the European Union to be controlled.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the audit of the administration of value added tax and excise duties for the years 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Control number: (CZ) 04 / 07 (SK) 18 / 2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Control of the procedure of the tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="18">On 11.2. 2004, a contract for cooperation in audit activities was concluded between the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as "SAO") and the Najvyššší kontrolní úrady Slovenskej republiky (hereinafter referred to as "SAO SR"). The object of the contract was cooperation in the parallel audit actions "Value Added Tax and Excise Tax," included in the SAO's audit activity plan for 2004 under No 04 / 07 and "Control of the procedure of the tax administration, control and enforcement of taxes on added value and spot taxes," included in the SAO SR's audit activity plan under No 18 / 2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information to the extent provided for in the contract concluded and the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the inspections.</seg>
<seg id="20">In the contract, the two parties undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the database of the customs administration and from the files of tax entities kept by the tax authorities in the Czech Republic and the tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the contracting parties could not obtain when checking the application of value added tax and excise duties on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the respective state.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic"), the inspection was carried out by the State Budget Department and the regional unions of South Bohemia, North-East Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited persons were the General Directorate of Customs and 12 selected tax offices: The Financial Office for Prague 1, the Financial Office for Prague 3, the Financial Office in České Budějovice, the Financial Office in Frýdek-Místek, the Financial Office in Hodonín, the Financial Office in Jihlava, the Financial Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Kroměříž, the Financial Office in Písek, the Financial Office in Rožnov pod Radhostem, the Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Velke Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "SR") was carried out by the Tax and Customs Administration Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with the expositions of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Bratislava Tax Office for selected tax entities, Bratislava III Tax Office, Trnava Tax Office, Pú-chov Tax Office, Banská Bystrica I Tax Office, Liptovský Mikuláš Tax Office, Žilina I Tax Office, Žilina II Tax Office, Košice I Tax Office and Košice IV Tax Office.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of control</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the control actions was to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of the tax and customs authorities in the administration of value added tax and excise duties, with a focus on the collection of these taxes on the import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of the international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic and their subsequent verification in tax returns at the respective tax and tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period covered the years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recap of inspection results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">In the framework of international cooperation, the SAO handed over 22,206 items of single customs declarations (hereinafter referred to as "JCDs") on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic from the Czech Republic's customs database, while the SAO handed over 30,221 items of JCDs from the Slovak Republic's customs database.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison was made between the designated JCD items from the Customs Database of the Czech Republic and the Customs Database of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="34">Of the 5,883 selected JCD items from the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, a total of 43% of the related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Out of the 12,343 selected JCD entries from the SR customs database, a total of 26% of the related JCD entries were allocated.</seg>
<seg id="36">On the basis of the non-allocated items of the JCD, a selection of the files of tax entities was carried out at the tax and tax offices, for which the declared imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="37">On the basis of the exchange of information from the documents of the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and the financial and tax authorities, the implementation of reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified in the territory of the second state.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO SR carried out a joint pilot inspection at the border customs crossing point Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma, in which the two parties worked closely together to verify the accuracy of data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="39">The audit did not find shortcomings in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods carried out in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation has made it possible to examine trade transactions between trading partners from both countries and has highlighted shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">Summary of the results of the inspection</seg>
<seg id="42">In the area of international cooperation, the audit of the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic focused on imports and exports of alcohol and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, and possibly other types of goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">Based on the audit of the files of tax entities at selected financial and tax offices, the SAO asked for verification of the implementation of exports of goods declared at 40 JCDs with a total statistical value of 15,301,093 CZK and the SAO asked the Slovak Republic for verification of exports with a statistical value of 56,989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and SAO SR found, among other things, the following facts:</seg>
<seg id="45">- trade transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the Czech customs database and the Slovak customs database,</seg>
<seg id="46">- an error in entering data into customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports or exports;</seg>
<seg id="47">- for some exports from the Czech Republic, corresponding imports to the Slovak Republic have not been demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="48">In such cases, there are reasonable grounds to suspect fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of improperly claiming deductions of value added tax;</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax entities have failed to comply with certain statutory obligations when declaring imports and exports in value added tax returns;</seg>
<seg id="50">- weaknesses have been identified in the activities of the tax and tax authorities in the administration of value added tax and excise duties and in their cooperation with the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the area of value added tax and excise duties, attention will continue to be paid to international trade in order to effectively minimise tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the activities of tax administrations in the administration of value added tax.</seg>
<seg id="53">Effective control of excise duties is based on the control of the circulation of documents, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information on the import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the situation in the field of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="55">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax ("VAT") was levied by the tax or tax authorities on taxable transactions carried out within the territory of the country and by the customs authorities on the importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">The tax revenue for the tax authorities was due to the difference between the collected own tax liability and the refunded excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenue at the customs offices was determined by the amount of tax collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">In accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, the tax collected by the customs authorities was reflected in the tax deductions applied to the tax authorities or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most tax and tax authorities, excess VAT deductions exceeded the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the key taxes in terms of state budget revenue, as it accounted for about 31% of the tax revenue of the state budget of the Czech Republic in 2003 and about 42% of the tax revenue of the state budget of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="62">The total VAT collection in the Czech Republic amounted to CZK 162.9 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="63">The tax and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 394.3 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions returned amounted to a total of CZK 231.4 billion.</seg>
<seg id="64">The total collection of VAT in the Slovak Republic amounted to CZK 83.8 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="65">In 2003, the tax and customs authorities collected Sk 187.0 billion in VAT and the excess VAT deductions recovered totalled Sk 103.2 billion.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise duties</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as "SPD") was carried out by the relevant tax and tax authorities and, on imports of products subject to SPD, by the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="68">The share of the SPD in the tax revenue of the state budget in the Czech Republic was about 16% in 2003 and about 19% in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of SPD collected in the Czech Republic by the tax and customs authorities in 2003 amounted to CZK 85.6 billion and in the Slovak Republic it amounted to CZK 38.0 billion.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. Progress of the control action</seg>
<seg id="71">Cooperation between the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, a comparison was made between imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic; in the second stage, the results of this comparison were used in the mutual verification of the implementation of selected commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and in the checks carried out on the territory of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of the control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel VAT and SPD checks was presented at a working meeting of representatives of the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">A coordination meeting took place in November 2003 at which, among other things, the selection of commodities - types of goods which posed a significant risk in compliance with customs and tax legislation was agreed: - ethyl alcohol and spirits, tariff headings 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, tariff headings 2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, tariff headings 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile phones and their accessories, tariff headings 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">Both parties agreed that the selection of tax entities for inspection will be carried out: (A) from non-allocated items found by comparing exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, (b) from entities carrying out imports and exports on a regular or one-off basis in large volumes, (c) on the basis of findings from inspections carried out by selected tax and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, the mechanism for cross-referencing JCD items registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was tested on a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, part of the exports from the Czech Republic were compared with imports into the Slovak Republic for 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the customs tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of 80% vol or more; ethyl alcohol and other spirits, denatured, of any strength,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of less than 80% vol; spirits, liqueurs and other spirituous beverages;</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unprocessed tobacco; tobacco waste;</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 Cigars (whether or not with the ends cut off), cigarillos and cigarettes of tobacco or tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other tobacco products and tobacco substitutes; homogenised or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and essences;</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmission apparatus containing reception equipment: For the cellular network (mobile phones),</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmission apparatus containing reception apparatus:</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts suitable for use solely or principally with the apparatus of headings 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Other: Parts of apparatus falling in subheadings 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">JCD items from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia were assigned to each other on the basis of the conformity of the individual paragraphs of the JCD (e.g. invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration number of the vehicle carrying the cargo, date of crossing of the national border, tariff item, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are presented in the following tables and graphs.</seg>
<seg id="92">The fact that trade transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides made it difficult, among other things, to match imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, exports from the Czech Republic, declared on one export JCD, were declared on several import JCDs in the territory of the Slovak Republic, or the export JCD had a different number of items from the import JCD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors that had an impact on the success of the assignment were the different composition of data in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, as well as the time difference between the registration of exports in the customs database of one country and the registration of corresponding imports in the customs database of another country.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples at the audited tax and tax offices respectively.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority was given to certain tax entities that carried out imports or exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, which could not be identified in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">In addition, some tax entities were selected for the verification of business transactions reported in VAT returns, where data on imports or exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic were found in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="98">4.3. Pilot check at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border crossing point</seg>
<seg id="99">The border customs crossing point for the performance of the pilot inspection was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of non-allocated JCD items in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="100">On the basis of a bilateral agreement between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, the use of control sheets has been introduced at border customs crossing points between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic since 1 June 1998.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate as far as possible customs and tax evasion, to provide an overview of the movement of means of transport carrying goods of a commercial nature in the customs area and to create the conditions for comparing customs records with each other.</seg>
<seg id="102">The joint pilot inspection was carried out between 8.3.2004 and 26.3.2004 and was aimed at examining this system of customs control.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for the use of checklists at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border crossing point:</seg>
<seg id="104">1) Weighing the vehicle, issuing a checklist and handing it over to the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Putting the vehicle in the designated sector in the parking lot.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs discussion in the check-in hall of the Police of the Czech Republic, Police of the Slovak Republic, Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The completion of the check-in process was confirmed by the individual files by stamping on the checklist.</seg>
<seg id="108">(3) Landing the vehicle in the area where the physical inspection is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="109">Presentation of the checklist, JCD or other documents to the customs official - check that all prescribed acts and documents have been carried out.</seg>
<seg id="110">Carrying out a physical check by the relevant services.</seg>
<seg id="111">Release of the vehicle from the customs area.</seg>
<seg id="112">When importing goods into the Czech Republic, the weighing of vehicles was carried out directly by the staff of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When the goods were imported into the Slovak Republic, the weighing of the vehicles was carried out by the staff of an authorised legal entity.</seg>
<seg id="114">After consideration, the vehicles were registered in a computerised register.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Exports from the Czech Republic to Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="117">The control sample was selected on the basis of an analysis of records from the customs database of exports of the Czech Republic in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the control sample for exports is shown in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">4.3.2. Checklists and their records Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="120">When exported from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic, the control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic recorded the registration numbers of these checklists in the electronic database of exports.</seg>
<seg id="122">Of the 453 JCD items, the SAO SR found 256 cases of imports into the Slovak Republic according to data from the customs database of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic. The remaining 197 JCD items were identified by the SAO SR in cooperation with the staff of the Drietoma border customs crossing.</seg>
<seg id="123">Exports from Slovakia to the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="124">When exporting from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, the control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">Out of a total of 339 JCD items of the selected audit sample, the SAO, in cooperation with the staff of the Starý Hrozenkov border customs crossing, assigned the corresponding registration numbers of the control sheets to 295 JCD items.</seg>
<seg id="126">The remaining 44 cases were identified in their records by the staff of the Drietoma border customs crossing and the export of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic was confirmed.</seg>
<seg id="127">The audit of the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic did not find shortcomings in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma border crossing point.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4. Selected control findings in the verification of commercial transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">In the framework of international cooperation, the implementation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified on the basis of documents from customs administrations and financial and tax authorities in the territory of the other country.</seg>
<seg id="130">For the selected tax entities, the following were verified:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia,</seg>
<seg id="132">- the fulfilment of the legal conditions for the application of the VAT deduction on importation, the refund of excess VAT and the application of the VAT exemption on exportation.</seg>
<seg id="133">The verification of the commercial transactions revealed:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. The SAO asked the Slovak Republic to verify the implementation of the export of alcohol with a statistical value of 56 989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified the corresponding imports in the Czech customs database with a statistical value of CZK 42,624.</seg>
<seg id="136">2. The company involved in the import and export of photographic equipment and accessories claimed an excess VAT deduction of CZK 3,740,664 in the VAT return for December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to check the reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO selected 3 JCDs (16 items) with a statistical value of CZK 1,274,822.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SAO SR identified 3 corresponding import JCDs (17 items) with a statistical value of 1,724,321 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="139">VAT was paid to the competent customs office in Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. The company, whose business was mainly trading in optical equipment, claimed in 2002 a total excess VAT deduction of CZK 4,1,36,000 higher than the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="141">The SAO selected an export JCD (32 items) with a statistical value of CZK 7,154,124 for the verification of the reported business activities.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SAO SR found that this JCD corresponds to an import JCD (12 items) with a statistical value of 9 653 827 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="143">VAT was paid to the competent customs office in Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. The company involved, inter alia, in the purchase of goods for resale and sale, did not declare any exports of goods in the VAT returns submitted in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 totalled CZK 3,439,888.</seg>
<seg id="146">Based on these facts, the SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 669,839 for verification.</seg>
<seg id="147">The SAO SR identified 5 corresponding import JCDs (5 items) with a statistical value of 1 012 656 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="148">An audit by the SAO of the Slovak Republic at the relevant tax office showed that the declared imports had been carried out and VAT paid.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. The company, whose business was, among other things, the purchase of goods for resale and sale, production, installation and repair of electrical machinery and equipment, reported exports of goods worth CZK 12,966,706 in VAT returns in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, the total value of exports in 2002 was 14,474,381 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO presented 17 export JCDs (59 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,975,122.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO SR identified 13 JCDs (50 items) in the SR customs database with a statistical value of 3 621 370 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="153">The SR customs database failed to identify the corresponding import JCDs for 4 export JCDs (9 items) with a total statistical value of 399,776 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="154">The competent tax office in Slovakia verified these imports with the tax entity.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity, listed on the JCD as an importer to the Slovak Republic, stated in the minutes of the local investigation that it did not carry out the imports declared on the Czech export JCDs.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO of the Slovak Republic therefore asked the local competent tax office to carry out a tax audit of VAT and corporate tax for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="157">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, the company involved in the import and sale of cigarettes exported tobacco stickers with a statistical value of 7,338,199 CZK in 2002 and 12,228,545 CZK in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="158">The company did not declare any exports in its VAT returns in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) for verification, with a total statistical value of CZK 2,471,598.</seg>
<seg id="160">In addition to the 4 export JCDs (4 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,246,860, the SAO SR identified 7 JCDs (7 items) with a statistical value of CZK 2,919,514 in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="161">The corresponding imports could not be attributed to the export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 224,738 in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="162">The software company did not declare exports of goods in its VAT returns for 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 and 2003 totalled CZK 1,630,198.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected 9 JCDs (9 items) for verification in the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of 755,588 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the SR customs database, the SAO SR identified 8 JCDs (8 items) with a statistical value of 915 601 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="166">The corresponding imports could not be attributed to the export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 68,286 in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="167">In these cases, it was not possible to identify in the SR customs database the corresponding imports to 6 JCDs with a statistical value of 692,800 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- for the 2 export JCDs from the Czech customs database with a statistical value of 293,024 CZK, the corresponding import JCDs could not be identified in the Slovak customs database (see paragraphs 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error rate in entering data into the customs database, it was not possible to identify some registered imports, e.g. in cases where the name of the importer was missing or there was an error in the tax identification number ("TIN").</seg>
<seg id="171">It is therefore not possible to conclude with certainty that those exports were not made.</seg>
<seg id="172">- 4 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic did not show imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a statistical value of 399,776 CZK (see paragraph 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In such cases, there are reasonable grounds to suspect the fictitious export of goods for the purpose of improperly claiming the VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services as part of the control of selected tax and tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of tax entities in respect of imports and exports of goods and services and to evaluate the level of cooperation between the tax and customs authorities, the files of tax entities were selected at the audited tax and tax offices according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. tax entities were selected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic: (A) with the highest volume of imports, (b) with the highest amount of VAT charged, (c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">(A) the VAT deductions applied on importation, (b) the excess VAT deductions applied, (c) the right to a refund of the SPD, (d) the VAT exemption applied on exportation,</seg>
<seg id="179">3. tax entities that have been subject to a tax audit.</seg>
<seg id="180">The sampling was carried out irrespective of the country of destination, with a focus on risky commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Control findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic for risky commodities in 2002 and 2003 is shown in the following table:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Control of the selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="184">At the audited tax offices, the SAO focused mainly on:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the procedure followed by the tax authorities to verify the accuracy of the VAT declared;</seg>
<seg id="186">- cooperation between the tax authorities and the customs administration;</seg>
<seg id="187">- comparing data from the customs database with the JCD database at the tax offices, focusing on comparing the declared value, applying the correct VAT rate following the customs classification of goods or services, or comparing data on the JCD and accompanying invoices with data in the customs database;</seg>
<seg id="188">- comparing data from VAT returns on transactions carried out and received from abroad with data in the JCD database at tax offices or in the customs database;</seg>
<seg id="189">- the method of verifying entitlement to VAT exemption on the export of goods or services abroad,</seg>
<seg id="190">- a comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services declared in VAT returns with data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The JCD database at the tax offices contained only records of those imports and exports for which tax entities were required to declare imports or exports on the tax return.</seg>
<seg id="192">The audited tax offices examined the files of tax entities, which reported imports totalling CZK 60,396,379,000 and corresponding VAT totalling CZK 12,644,052,000 in VAT returns in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="193">In addition, the files of tax entities reporting exports worth a total of CZK 47,323,111,000 in tax returns for 2002 and 2003 were checked.</seg>
<seg id="194">According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, in 2002 and 2003, the tax entities for which imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic were examined carried out imports into the Czech Republic from the Slovak Republic with a total VAT base of CZK 3,759,352,000, VAT of CZK 767,607,000 and exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of CZK 1,989,090,000.</seg>
<seg id="195">The observed differences between the records in the JCD database at the tax offices and in the customs database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- JCD items that were missing from the Czech customs database were requested directly from the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="197">- JCD items that were missing from the tax authorities' database were checked for cancelled documents;</seg>
<seg id="198">- for JCD items, which were found to have different values between the customs database of the Czech Republic and the database of the tax authorities, the relevant JCD was requested from the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic in written form, including the attached invoices.</seg>
<seg id="199">The investigation revealed that the JCD database at the tax offices did not contain, for example, records of import JCDs with a total value of VAT of CZK 3,622,000 and records of export JCDs with a total statistical value of CZK 9,359,000.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Differences identified</seg>
<seg id="201">A comparison of the JCD database at the tax offices and the cumulative tax liability for 2002 and 2003 in the VAT returns of a selected sample of tax entities revealed the following differences:</seg>
<seg id="202">The differences in values were mainly due to:</seg>
<seg id="203">- The time lag between the realisation of imports and the exercise of the right to deduct the VAT charged on the importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The taxable person could exercise the right to deduct on importation of the goods within 3 years of the end of the tax year in which the goods were placed under the relevant procedure or, in the case of the temporary importation procedure, within 3 years of the end of the tax year in which the procedure ended.</seg>
<seg id="205">- The time lag between the realisation of the export and the moment when the taxpayer received the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The taxpayer was obliged to enter data on realised exports exempt from the obligation to apply output tax in the VAT return at the earliest for the tax year in which the goods left the country, if he also had a tax document, which was a JCD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- Failure to comply with the obligations of tax entities when declaring imports and exports in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, tax entities did not provide correct data on imports and exports in their VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">As tax entities did not have to attach JCD lists to the VAT returns submitted, the control of the right to deduct VAT or the exemption from VAT by the tax authorities was made more difficult.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2. Cooperation between financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">During the audited period, import or export duties and VAT were repaid or remitted on the basis of decisions taken by the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="212">The tax entities were required by law to reduce the previously exercised right to deduct VAT by the amount of tax returned by the customs office in the tax return for the period in which the tax was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legislation provided for information on changes in the level of customs duties and VAT to be sent from customs offices to tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some of the audited tax offices received this information, but irregularly or with considerable delays, and only from some customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited tax office did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information about changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the data necessary to check compliance with the legal obligation of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002 the customs authorities returned VAT in the amount of more than CZK 319 million and in 2003 in the amount of more than CZK 398 million.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the audit revealed persistent shortcomings in the activities of the tax authorities, some systemic errors in the cooperation of the tax authorities with the customs authorities and the failure to comply with certain obligations of taxpayers submitting VAT returns and the SPD.</seg>
<seg id="219">Weaknesses were identified in the VAT and SPD administration, in particular in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="220">(A) when VAT registrations are cancelled, the fulfilment of the obligation of the payers to pay VAT on the business property registered or which should have been registered on the date of the deregistration, for which the payer claimed the deduction, was only rarely verified;</seg>
<seg id="221">(B) the tax authorities have not consistently used the possibility to carry out a tax audit or a local investigation.</seg>
<seg id="222">This has in some cases led to a lack of verification of the right to deduct VAT;</seg>
<seg id="223">(C) the official records and minutes of the oral hearing do not contain all the necessary information to prove the validity of the excess VAT deductions claimed;</seg>
<seg id="224">(D) the tax authorities have not sufficiently verified the imports and exports declared in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. Control findings in SR</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Control of the selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">For the selected sample, the SAO audited or the tax office carried out a tax audit for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analysing the submitted tax returns and requests for tax refunds from selected tax entities, the SAO asked the tax office to secure the relevant JCDs showing imports and exports, invoices and proof of payment of the tax.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, the SAO SR checked whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs database of imports and exports and the fulfilment of the decisive facts and legal conditions for the application of the deduction of input tax in respect of imports, for the refund of excess VAT, for the application of the export tax exemption and for the reimbursement of SPD.</seg>
<seg id="230">At the 10 tax offices audited, the SAO of the Slovak Republic verified selected cases of imports and exports of goods between the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in a structure according to the honour of JCD items and the sum of statistical values shown in the table below.</seg>
<seg id="231">In total, imports with a statistical value of CZK 856.2 million were checked, which represents 5.11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic to SROV.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were checked for a total statistical value of 176 million SK, which represents 6.87% of the total value of exports of selected commodities from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="233">In addition, 618 cases of imports of other goods and services (mainly white technology, packaging technology and software) from EU countries to the Slovak Republic were checked for a total statistical value of 532.8 million SK.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Cooperation between tax and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="235">The SAO of the Slovak Republic's audit at the tax offices found discrepancies between the data registered in the Slovak customs database and the data reported in specific VAT returns, e.g.:</seg>
<seg id="236">- 2 tax entities (natural persons) declared imports of goods with a total value of Sk 1 589 261 in their tax returns, on the basis of which they claimed a refund of excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="237">In local investigations carried out at the initiative of the SAO SR, tax entities were not able to prove to the tax office that the application of the input tax was justified by the relevant documents on the realisation of imports and the payment of VAT,</seg>
<seg id="238">- in the tax return for the tax year January 2003, the tax entity (s. r. o.) declared the taxable transaction received in the value of 77 167 576 Sk, the export of goods in the value of 18 006 041 Sk and claimed an excess VAT deduction of 17 157 101 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="239">According to the VAT returns submitted for 2003, the difference between the volume of purchases and exports of Sk 59 161 535, which arose in January 2003, was not made up during the whole of 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the cases mentioned above, the SAO asked the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of the excess VAT deductions applied.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, the tax entity (s. r. o.) for the tax period January to June 2002 stated in the VAT returns the export of goods with a total value of 87 199 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="242">A verification in the SR customs database revealed that the tax entity had made exports with a statistical value of SKK 296 747 during the period.</seg>
<seg id="243">The Tax Office carried out a number of local inquiries at the company's head office, finding that the manager of the company (a UK citizen) had travelled and the company had left the rented premises without terminating the lease in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of the audit of the SAO SR, the tax administration filed a complaint with the law enforcement authorities on suspicion of the crime of non-payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="245">Based on the results of the audit at the selected tax offices, the SAO SR notes that the biggest problems in the performance of the administration and control of VAT and SPD occurred mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- not making use of the possibility to carry out VAT checks on problematic tax entities, in particular in cases where the high value of excess VAT deductions is applied;</seg>
<seg id="247">- the tax inspection reports did not contain an inventory of the audited documents</seg>
<seg id="248">- JCDs for the import and export of goods;</seg>
<seg id="249">- insufficient verification of declared imports and exports of goods in tax returns;</seg>
<seg id="250">- lengthy procedures for tax administrations to issue decisions, in particular in the context of the assessment procedure, with the consequence that the right to impose penalties ceases to exist;</seg>
<seg id="251">- failure to comply with legal conditions when granting tax deferrals;</seg>
<seg id="252">- failure to compensate for VAT arrears by the deadline for the refund of excess VAT;</seg>
<seg id="253">- under-utilisation of all forms of security and recovery of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">On the basis of the findings of the audit, the SAO asked the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax audit of VAT, focusing on the legitimacy of the claimed excess VAT deductions for 14 tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="255">At all audited tax offices, measures have been taken to remedy the shortcomings identified by the audit, the implementation of which will be monitored and audited by the SAO.</seg>
<seg id="256">6. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation has made it possible to examine trade transactions between trading partners from both countries and has highlighted shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="258">The inspections also resulted in the identification of persistent deficiencies in the performance of VAT and SPD obligations, in the activities of the tax and tax authorities, in the system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax and customs authorities, which ultimately reduced the efficiency and effectiveness of tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="259">The findings also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have basic data on imports and exports from the customs database of the Czech Republic as part of the tax information system. In the Slovak Republic, there is no similar system for transmitting information on imports and exports of goods between the customs and tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the performance of the VAT administration and the SPD was not the same, due to the different legislation and conditions in the territory of the two states.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from information obtained at the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic and from documents available at the audited tax offices. The SAO of the Slovak Republic verified the execution of business transactions from documents of tax entities requested through the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="262">If irregularities were found, he asked the tax authorities to carry out tax checks.</seg>
<seg id="263">The parallel VAT and SPD checks carried out assessed the state of the administration of these taxes in the period before accession to the European Union and pointed to the need for further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will be further enhanced in the monitoring of the activities of the tax and tax authorities in the context of the adoption of the new VAT law.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations related to the delivery of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of a so-called summary report.</seg>
<seg id="266">This declaration must be made by all VAT payers who have made a supply of goods to another Member State to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax administrations are required to enter data from recapitulative statements into the VAT Information Exchange System (VIES), which is accessible to tax administrations from Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="268">The tax and tax authorities then have the opportunity to compare these data with the data contained in the VAT returns submitted.</seg>
<seg id="269">This system is also used to verify the validity of the VAT registration number of persons registered for VAT, to verify the validity of the VAT exemption applied when goods are delivered to another Member State and to check the proper taxation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel audit actions has shown the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these control actions will be confronted with the results of the planned control actions, which will focus, among other things, on the examination of the VIES system, which is designed to prevent tax evasion in so-called "intra-community supplies."</seg>
<seg id="272">Given the importance of VAT and SPD for budgetary revenue, control activities need to focus primarily on monitoring and identifying risk areas in order to reduce the scope for tax evasion in indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was drawn up in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office and the Chairman of the Najvyššššie Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
