<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of checks at asylum facilities in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">State property and funds intended to secure the activities of the Refugee Facilities Administration of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="3">Control Action No 04 / 23 "State property and funds intended to ensure the activities of the Refugee Facilities Administration of the Ministry of the Interior"</seg>
<seg id="4">Control action No 15 / 2004 "Control of the economy with staff and financial resources for the provision of asylum and temporary refuge in the Slovak Republic"</seg>
<seg id="5">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">Population migration is one of the global phenomena that has become an inseparable part of the current development phase of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">This is mainly due to the flight of citizens from their country of origin or last permanent residence from persecution, in particular for reasons of race, religion, nationality, politics, as well as the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Their aim is to gain asylum and integration into society, especially in one of the advanced democratic countries of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="9">A large group is also made up of foreigners, whose migration is due to unfavourable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The adoption of the 1951 Geneva Agreement and the 1967 New York Protocol on the Status of Refugees, the acceptance of which the governments of the signatory countries undertook to apply in their foreign policy orientation, has already resulted in the establishment of specific principles for refugee assistance.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federal Republics ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">After the separation in 1993, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue by continuing to comply with accepted international documents and confirmed their binding force under national legislation by a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both Republics have also enshrined the granting of asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">Parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyššší kontrolný úradom Slovenskej republiky, the results of which are contained in the joint final report, focused on the asylum process and related issues.</seg>
<seg id="16">The cooperation between the supreme audit authorities of the two countries was carried out on the basis of the "Treaty on Cooperation in Control Activities" (hereinafter referred to as "the Treaty") concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">In the Treaty, the two Parties undertook to provide each other with information on the legislation governing the asylum procedure in the State of the other Party, selected statistics on the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as information on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the parallel control action was to identify the same problem areas and to highlight the consequences for the area of population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted in the unification of the programme of control actions, the exchange of information to the extent provided for by the Treaty and the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">The first joint meeting, which took place from 5.4 to 7.4.2004, set out the same areas of control issues and control procedures for the preparation of control actions.</seg>
<seg id="21">At the second meeting, which took place from 28.6 to 30.6. 2004, the common items for the programme of the control action were specified.</seg>
<seg id="22">During the third joint meeting, which took place during the inspection mission from 8.11 to 10.11.2004, there was an exchange of experience on the ongoing inspections.</seg>
<seg id="23">The modalities of the outcome of the checks have been specified and the structure and content of the joint final report, which was drawn up from 14.2. to 17.2.2005 at the last joint meeting, has been provisionally established.</seg>
<seg id="24">The checks were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, the inspection was carried out by inspectors of the Department of Defence and Security and selected territorial departments.</seg>
<seg id="26">The audited persons were the Ministry of the Interior ("MV") and the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior ("SUZ").</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic, it carried out inspections of the defence section, vnútra and štátnych úradov.</seg>
<seg id="28">The audited entity was the Migračný úrad Ministerstvo vnútra SR ("MÚ").</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period covered the years 2001, 2002 and 2003 (the audited period).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistical data over a longer period of time are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2. Recap of inspection results</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. Evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of parallel checks was: - the asylum process, - asylum facilities, - the management of state funds and assets, - the internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of experience between the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyššší kontrolní úradom Slovenskej republiky took place at the stage of preparation and implementation of the control actions.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange allowed for a more thorough evaluation of the submitted supporting documents, an analysis of the causes of the identified differences in the security of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">In this way, it was possible to focus on the critical problems affecting the activities of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">In the end, this had a positive effect on the quality of the control work carried out.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonisation of the asylum laws of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with European Union (EU) documents was the subject of evaluation reports by the European Commission on the readiness of both countries to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">The adoption of legislation in this area continues after the accession of the two countries to the EU with a view to further harmonisation with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants has been on a steadily increasing trend, with a significant increase in applicants in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">Within the meaning of international agreements, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic provide financial and material security for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="44">The national budgets of both countries allocate the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditure drawn from the state budget of both countries is mainly influenced by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until asylum is granted or not granted, as well as the state of health of the applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">Some of the doses collected are comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic have set up asylum facilities in which they have gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of participants in asylum procedures.</seg>
<seg id="48">During their stay, asylum seekers are provided with accommodation, meals, health care and basic material and hygiene equipment.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, courses are organised as part of leisure activities and the conditions for cultural and sporting activities are created for applicants.</seg>
<seg id="50">Asylum facilities include reception centres and residential centres as well as integration centres in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cost per day of stay depends on the occupancy and equipment of the centre and is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is basically stable.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is expected to increase by almost 1 000 jobs in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create the conditions for applicants, an increasing number of whom are expected to continue in the coming years in the context of the application of the Dublin Convention.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the highest part of the approved budget expenditure was spent on the provision of services. The decisive expenditure of this item was expenditure on accommodation and meals for applicants in asylum facilities operated under contract, expenditure on health care provided to asylum seekers and the cost of a permanent security service ensuring the protection of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">Expenditure on salaries, payments for work carried out and insurance premiums also accounted for a significant share of total expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of the security of migration policy and the asylum process was marked by a number of budgetary measures addressing legitimate demands related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Expenditure on wages, salaries and insurance premiums, expenditure on materials and services and expenditure on security services were a decisive factor in the absorption of current expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic highlighted some similar shortcomings which did not have a major impact on the financial management and management of the state's assets.</seg>
<seg id="60">These were mainly shortcomings in the use of state budget funds, contrary to the purpose for which they were determined by the State Budget Act, when current expenditure was used to cover actions in the nature of technical evaluation of fixed tangible assets.</seg>
<seg id="61">The Act on Accounting in the Field of Inventory and Non-Compliance with the Accounting Curriculum was also violated.</seg>
<seg id="62">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were also found in the disposal of state property when it was transferred to another person without a contract.</seg>
<seg id="63">Failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes in land registry data violated the Land Registry Act and the Waste Act was violated by leaving waste for disposal to a person who was not a person authorised for waste management.</seg>
<seg id="64">In the Slovak Republic, deficiencies were also found in the provision of excessively high advances for the collection of electricity and natural gas, deficiencies in the award of public contracts and in the management of the state's assets, when its records were not sufficiently secured and the method of liquidating unnecessary assets was not demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="65">The internal control system has been ensured in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic within the meaning of the generally binding legislation in force governing the way financial control is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="66">No deficiencies were found in the written documentation submitted.</seg>
<seg id="67">Despite some shortcomings identified, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší kontrolný úrad Slovenské republiky are positive about the progress of SUZ and MÚ in providing services for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="68">Based on the lessons learned during the inspection, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyššší kontrolný úrad Slovenské republiky note that despite a significant increase in the number of asylum seekers in recent years, the respective organisational units of both countries have managed the tasks related to the care of asylum seekers at an appropriate level.</seg>
<seg id="69">The evaluation shows that the system is functional and stable.</seg>
<seg id="70">The results of the inspection were discussed with the interested statutory representatives of the relevant organisational units of the state on both the Czech and Slovak sides.</seg>
<seg id="71">Based on the results of the inspection, we recommend that the positive methodological experience of the inspection be used in other joint control actions within the framework of international cooperation between supreme audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="72">3. Legislative framework</seg>
<seg id="73">In both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, asylum law is based on the 1951 Geneva Convention (the Convention relating to the Status of Refugees and the subsequent 1967 New York Protocol).</seg>
<seg id="74">The first legislation was implemented by Act No 498 / 1990 Coll., on Refugees.</seg>
<seg id="75">In the Czech Republic, Act No. 325 / 1999 Coll., on Asylum and amending Act No. 83 / 1991 Coll., on the Police of the Czech Republic, has been in force since 1 January 2000.</seg>
<seg id="76">This law has been amended five times (Act No. 2 / 2002 Coll., Act No. 217 / 2002 Coll., Act No. 320 / 2002 Coll., Act No. 519 / 2002 Coll., and Act No. 222 / 2003 Coll.).</seg>
