<seg id="226">6.2 Deficiencies identified</seg>
<seg id="227">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic pointed to some similar shortcomings which did not have a major impact on the management of the state's funds and assets.</seg>
<seg id="228">These were mainly shortcomings in the following areas: (A) the use of state budget funds contrary to the purpose for which they were intended by the State Budget Act, when current expenditure was used to cover actions having the character of a technical evaluation of fixed tangible assets; (b) the violation of the Accounting Act in the field of inventories and the failure to comply with the indicative chart of accounts.</seg>
<seg id="229">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were also found in the management of state property, where it was left for use by another person without a proper contract; failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes to land registry data violated the Land Registry Act; leaving waste for disposal to a person who was not a person entitled to waste management violated the Waste Act.</seg>
<seg id="230">In addition, in the Slovak Republic, deficiencies were found in the provision of excessively high advances for the collection of electricity and natural gas, deficiencies in the award of public contracts and in the management of the state's assets, when its records were not sufficiently secured and the method of liquidating unnecessary assets was not demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="231">7. Internal control system</seg>
<seg id="232">In the Czech Republic, an internal control system within the meaning of the provisions of Act No. 320 / 2001 Coll., on Financial Control, was introduced at SUZ as of 1.7. 2002, setting out the competencies of individual employees responsible for carrying out preliminary, ongoing and follow-up checks.</seg>
