<p>
<seg id="1">Joint Report on Parallel Controls of Expenditure on Construction of the Prague-Dresden Motorway</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">Without trans-European transport networks, it would be difficult to imagine a modern, dynamic and, above all, united Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">High-quality transport networks are a prerequisite for maintaining and raising the standard of living of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating the conditions for fast, safe, reliable and cheap transport of passengers and freight is an important task for the state administration.</seg>
<seg id="6">It is a very demanding task, both in organisational and technical terms and in financial terms.</seg>
<seg id="7">European efforts at sustainable mobility often find it difficult to compromise with Europe's interest in maintaining a healthy and human-friendly environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">The construction of transport infrastructure, even with the necessary measures for the benefit of the environment, is expensive.</seg>
<seg id="9">The considered procedures and decisions of the state administration in the preparation and acquisition of transport works can bring significant savings in public financial resources, which can be used differently for the benefit of citizens.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of audit institutions is to actively look for deficiencies that have led to lower than achievable economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure on the construction of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit institutions should not only draw the attention of the state administration to the shortcomings identified, but recommend measures to improve the situation, for the benefit of the citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two highest audit institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (Germany and the Czech Republic), the Bundesrechnungshof (BRH) and the Supreme Audit Office (SAO), carried out parallel checks on expenditure on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (D 8 motorway in the Czech Republic and A 17 motorway in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The motorways are connected by a border bridge, which is co-financed by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to the cooperation with the SAO, BRH was able to carry out a thorough audit of the effectiveness of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">On the basis of close cooperation with BRH, the SAO obtained the necessary data on the amount of German costs for bridges and tunnels for comparative purposes.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded a contract for the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the construction process, the completion date was finally scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, in the course of the award of the contract, the Road and Motorway Directorate of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the SDD") made mistakes which led to an extension of the competition period and a reduction in the construction period.</seg>
<seg id="20">As a result, the contract with the contractor was signed later than expected.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter period of time and to ensure its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, however, the SDD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint inspection work, the prices of bridges on the D 8 and A 17 motorways were compared on the basis of the per m2 area of the bridge structure.</seg>
<seg id="24">Statistical analysis of prices has made it possible to identify bridges with high costs per square metre of area.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in a group of large bridges with a length of more than 100 metres.</seg>
<seg id="26">The price increase could also be attributed to a delay in the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="27">When analysing the cost of building the tunnels, the auditors found that the prices of the tunnels on the D 8 motorway were significantly higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">BRH and the SAO now have a database on the prices of bridges and tunnels, which they will be able to rely on for future checks on the effectiveness of the funds used for transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="29">For the construction of bridges, both control institutions recommend: Standardization of bridge construction and use of coupled steel concrete and special structures only in cases where pre-stressed reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">One of the main features of cooperation was its team spirit and informality.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the course of the parallel inspection, the inspectors shared their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report reports on the progress and results of parallel checks on the funds spent on the construction of the motorway connecting Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The controls focused on the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of the expenditure incurred.</seg>
<seg id="35">Parallel inspections were carried out by BRH in Germany and the SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="36">Parallel checks were carried out in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The SAO audited the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure amounting to approximately CZK 20 billion, including VAT (approximately €690 million) on the border section of the D 8 motorway, which has the number 0807.</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, €64 million was planned to be used from European funds (ISPA).</seg>
<seg id="39">In addition to a parallel audit carried out jointly with the SAO, BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The funds spent on the construction of all three sections of the A17 motorway amounted to around €670 million, of which €277 million will be co-financed by European funds (ERDF).</seg>
<seg id="41">The motorway from Prague to Dresden is part of the Trans-European Transport Corridor IV Dresden - the central and southern parts of Eastern Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D8 motorway runs from Prague through Ústí nad Labem to the state border.</seg>
<seg id="43">The A17 motorway runs from the state border of the Czech Republic / Germany to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the inspection, the border sections of the two motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">These sections became operational on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">On the German side, the motorway is thus completed all the way to Dresden, while on the Czech side of the D 8 motorway it is not completed, as section 0805 of 16.4 km through the Bohemian Central Mountains between Řehlovice and Lovosice is still in the preparatory phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">According to the plan, section 0805 between Prague and Ústí nad Labem is to pass through the protected landscape area of the Czech Central Mountains.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to forecasts made in the Czech Republic in 2001, the traffic intensity on the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway should be 22,940 vehicles per day in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="49">According to German forecasts, the traffic intensity at the Czech border will total about 25,000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, Germany and the Czech Republic concluded an agreement between the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic on the interconnection of the German motorway A 17 and the Czech motorway D 8 on the common state border by the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Both states are involved in the construction of the bridge, so the control of the construction of the bridge was an important aspect of the parallel checks carried out by the two control institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and the SAO</seg>
<seg id="53">Since mid-2005, the two supreme audit institutions have been discussing close cooperation in the control of the construction of the motorway connecting Prague and Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="54">There were serious reasons for both parties to cooperate:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany is financially involved in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Its planning and construction is based on the SDD.</seg>
<seg id="58">Therefore, BRH itself did not have the opportunity to carry out an inspection of the construction project.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The SAO did not have the comparative database needed to assess whether the funds were used economically in terms of the overall level of costs of bridges and tunnels on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO needed to ascertain the effectiveness of the expenditure, taking into account the main technical parameters of the motorway, especially the arrangement of bridges and tunnels, which should allow the same quality of travel on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">Following preparatory negotiations, the Agreement on the coordinated control of the D 8 / A 17 motorway was signed on 4 January 2006 by the presidents of the two supreme audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="64">The joint working meetings between the auditors of BRH and the SAO took place over the whole of 2006 at an interval of approximately six to eight weeks.</seg>
<seg id="65">The meetings addressed current problems and challenges, in particular the preparation of a uniform methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels, the exchange of findings from the inspection of the construction of the border bridge and the preparation of joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">The continuous exchange of information was an important feature of the cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="67">While BRH carried out most of the work on comparing the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels and the tender procedure, the SAO largely prepared a methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels.</seg>
<seg id="68">The applicable legal standards for control in the civil service differ in the way control actions are concluded in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="69">For these reasons, the two supreme audit institutions have drawn up their own audit conclusions on their findings during their inspections.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report reflects the results achieved by the parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation will end with the signing of the final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In a 2000 agreement, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed on a date for the completion of the construction of the border bridge, as far as possible, in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="74">The two sides then agreed to postpone this deadline until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The SDD acted as an investor.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany has a 42.13% financial stake in the construction of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the period up to 1999, the SDD proposed that the border bridge should have a prestressed reinforced concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, in agreement with its partners in Germany, the SDD agreed to a coupled steel and concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">This decision was justified by the reduction of the number of double pillars from seven to five and the consequent environmental benefits of such a solution for the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, the comparative calculations carried out by the SDD stated that the coupled steel concrete structure should be a less expensive option.</seg>
<seg id="81">But there was an error in the calculations.</seg>
<seg id="82">They stated that the new jointed steel concrete structure would be only 397 m long.</seg>
<seg id="83">In fact, it's 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">In the course of awarding the contract for the border bridge, the SDD made serious errors.</seg>
<seg id="85">It did not prepare contract documents that adequately described the assessment criteria and the sub-criteria for the comparison of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="86">This error led to a subjective and problematic evaluation of bids by the bid assessment and evaluation committee and the CEO.</seg>
<seg id="87">The unsuccessful tenderer contested the results of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">A subsequent investigation by the Office for the Protection of Competition led to the contract for the construction contract being signed later than originally planned.</seg>
<seg id="89">This meant that the 2004 summer construction season, after bids were evaluated, was wasted and construction time was reduced.</seg>
<seg id="90">The construction company agreed to build the bridge in a shorter period of time, but at the cost of a substantial increase in costs.</seg>
<seg id="91">The procedure offered included the double installation of the bridge top, a change in the construction of the pillars and the installation and equipment of the assembly areas.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the construction company was not able to procure the originally designed type of steel within the necessary time.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel - at a price higher by about €4 million, which had to be paid in full by the SDD - made it possible to reduce the time for the implementation of anti-corrosion protection, which in turn made it possible to reduce the total construction time of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the net price of €18.3 million offered in the tender, the total cost of the construction of the border bridge will increase considerably as a result of the accelerated procedure and other adjustments in funding.</seg>
<seg id="95">The reduced time allocated to construction work has led to a price increase of about €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">The net cost is currently around €25.9 million, without taking into account automatic price increases (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of prices of bridges and tunnels</seg>
<seg id="98">The two supreme audit institutions analysed the prices of bridges on the D 8 and A 17 motorways in order to identify bridges whose price was too high and to compare the prices of bridges on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The analysis was based on mathematical statistical methods.</seg>
<seg id="100">In addition, the tunnels on D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on motorways in Germany (A 71, A 38 and A 4).</seg>
<seg id="101">There are no similar tunnels on the A17.</seg>
<seg id="102">In the preparation of this part of the inspection, it was important to identify precisely the relevant prices.</seg>
<seg id="103">The two supreme audit institutions have set the following principles for comparing the prices of bridges: Based on the actual price paid for the bridge, excluding value added tax (VAT rates vary in the Czech Republic and the SNR and are subject to changes); do not take into account the prices for the special foundations of the bridge; recalculate the prices in CZK to €according to the rate of the European Central Bank applicable on 30 December 2005 (CZK 29 = €1).</seg>
<seg id="104">On both D 8 and A 17 there are bridges of different structures (steel concrete, prestressed reinforced concrete, coupled steel and steel) and of different sizes.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure the homogeneity of the structures examined, the bridges were divided into groups according to the type of structure.</seg>
<seg id="106">Within these groups, the size of the bridge was also taken into account in the analyses.</seg>
<seg id="107">Concrete bridges were by far the most common type of construction on both sides of the border (20 bridges on D 8, 36 bridges on A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The analysis focused mainly on this group of bridges, as the size of the population allowed the use of mathematical and statistical methods with a high degree of reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The inspections found that prices per m 2 of concrete bridges on both D 8 and A 17 depend on the size of the bridge (its length, area): The larger the bridge, the lower the price per m2 of bridge construction.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the price's dependence on size was stronger than for Czech bridges (see graphs below).</seg>
<seg id="111">Two concrete bridges on A 17 and four on D 8 have been identified, the price of which is significantly higher.</seg>
<seg id="112">In order to find these bridges, a method was used to detect atypical values in a set of numbers and a regression analysis taking into account the dependence of the price of the bridge on its size (the distance from the regression curve upwards is decisive for determining atypical expensive bridges).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, information on the atypical high price of these bridges should only be considered as an indicator of which bridges need to be targeted.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw a generally applicable conclusion, the reasons for the high price in each case identified should be analysed.</seg>
<seg id="115">One such cause may be inefficient administrative measures, or environmental protection requirements or any other acceptable reason.</seg>
<seg id="116">In view of the fact that Czech concrete bridges are on average longer than German bridges (see table below), the proven negative dependence of the bridge price on its length could lead to the assumption that Czech bridges should be cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">The hypothesis of lower prices of Czech concrete bridges is also supported by lower labour costs in the construction sector in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">On the contrary, the results of the analysis show that the prices of concrete bridges on D 8 are higher than on A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">In the course of the joint negotiations, two possible causes of this situation were identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, most bridges are awarded as separate contracts.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such an award allows small and medium-sized regional firms to take part in the competition for the contract.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridges are awarded as part of the contract for part of the motorway route, which is several kilometres long.</seg>
<seg id="124">Small and medium-sized companies do not participate in such a competition because the contract is too big for them.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">In the Czech Republic, there is more variability in the construction of bridges than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the SAO found that the type of construction of the bridge is decided long before its construction.</seg>
<seg id="128">The decision is taken at the time when the application for a territorial decision is submitted by the SDD.</seg>
<seg id="129">At this time, the SDD selects types of bridges from several options, but economy plays a smaller role in the decision.</seg>
<seg id="130">A general conclusion on the prices of bridges in the Czech Republic and Germany could only be drawn on the basis of a thorough analysis of the construction market in both countries, which would, however, go beyond the scope of this inspection.</seg>
<seg id="131">The Boundary Bridge is the most expensive combined steel concrete bridge on D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of tunnels, the prices of tunnels on D 8 were found to be twice as high as those in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the main construction-technical parameters of the tunnels on D 8 with the tunnels in Germany did not show any significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">Significant price differences could be attributed to the fact that there is no real competition in the construction of tunnels in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not make it possible to draw generally applicable conclusions.</seg>
<seg id="136">Effectiveness and efficiency of the construction of the Dresden - Prague motorway</seg>
<seg id="137">The independent Czech Republic was established in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government approved a concept for the development of the motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">The D8 motorway was to be gradually extended from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section 0805 through the Czech Central Mountains should have been acquired before the border section 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic procures the D 8 motorway as part of its programme funding.</seg>
<seg id="142">The programme No 327 220 "Construction of the D 8 motorway Prague - Ústí nad Labem - state border of the Czech Republic / Germany" set out two objectives for the construction of the D 8 motorway:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">Improve the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem - a national objective;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">Improve connections between Prague and Berlin in the framework of the 4th Trans-European Transport Corridor Berlin-Istanbul - an international goal.</seg>
<seg id="147">According to the programme, the construction of the section running through the Czech Central Mountains was to be completed in June 2008 and the construction of the border section 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be added here that the completion date is not the same as the commissioning date.</seg>
<seg id="149">The SAO found that the preparation of the construction of the section running through the Czech Central Mountains is now at the stage of an official planning decision.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental activists have challenged the decision with lawsuits.</seg>
<seg id="151">There is no final decision on the actions.</seg>
<seg id="152">It cannot therefore be ruled out that the section running through the Czech Central Mountains will be completed several years later than stated in the documentation of the programme.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed to postpone the completion date of section 0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result of these facts, the construction of the border section did not achieve the national goal of improving the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The SDD carried out an estimate of the capital expenditure for the border section D 8 no. 0807 and the section no. 0805 through the Bohemian Central Mountains in the years 1999-2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">The estimated capital expenditure included in the investment costs is about €639 million for both sections 0805 and 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Results of the economic assessment (EIRR)</seg>
<seg id="158">All motorways and expressways under consideration are open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">On the northern part of the border section, traffic intensity of 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="160">All motorways and expressways under consideration are open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">On the northern part of the border section, traffic intensity of 22 000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="162">All motorways and expressways under consideration are open, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">On the northern part of the border section, traffic intensity of 25 000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="164">The economic analysis carried out in 2001 was based on the assumption that the border section and the section through the Czech Central Mountains would be completed in time.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of the inspection, however, it is clear that the section through the Czech Central Mountains will not be opened on the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This will reduce the above EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">The cost of both sections, net of VAT, calculated as at 31 December 2005, was €897 million, i.e. higher by 27.4% than the cost level used in the economic analysis in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="168">However, there is a risk that section 0805 will run on a different, more expensive route, which would affect the above-mentioned threshold of economic viability.</seg>
<seg id="169">Economic analysis has shown that the construction of both sections of motorway is economically viable with a traffic intensity of at least 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="170">The forecast for 2008 was 22,940 vehicles, but a study addressing the issue of bypass routes for the missing section through the Bohemian Central Mountains projects a traffic intensity of 12,600 to 13,750 vehicles per day, pushing the investment below the limit of economic viability.</seg>
<seg id="171">There is a high probability of congestion and thus an increase in external costs, which were not foreseen in the original economic analysis, due to the higher load on the bypass routes for the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains.</seg>
<seg id="172">The aforementioned reduction in revenues and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR that the construction of the border section D 8 was expected to have will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">Construction of the D 8 border section is before inefficent.</seg>
<seg id="174">The construction of the A 17 motorway also resulted in cost overruns similar to those of the two sections on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the overall economic assessment of the Federal Road Development Plan for long-distance transport for 1992, the Federal Ministry of Transport of Germany estimated the cost to be around €320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">The resulting cost-benefit ratio was 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, however, costs have risen sharply to around €670 million, reducing the cost-benefit ratio by more than half.</seg>
<seg id="178">In addition to a parallel audit carried out jointly with the SAO, BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="179">In doing so, the BRH found that the competent approval state authority had requested an off-road tunnel for Section A 17, which was not needed.</seg>
<seg id="180">During the inspection, BRH was able to convince the Federal Ministry and the German Road Administration that the tunnel was not necessary.</seg>
<seg id="181">This resulted in savings of around €10 million in construction costs alone and €0.15 million in annual operating costs.</seg>
<seg id="182">In its assessment of the first section A 17, BRH found that the construction project had not been properly prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">This is illustrated by the following example:</seg>
<seg id="184">At the preparatory stage, the Road Administration did not carry out a survey of the conditions of the bedrock in the Dölzschen rocks, as the site was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">This was carried out only after the tunnel stamping machine hit the rock.</seg>
<seg id="186">Tests have shown that the rocks inside are more weathered than expected during the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="187">As a result, costly measures such as anchoring, injection and stone-fall protection nets had to be taken, costing about €3.3 million.</seg>
<seg id="188">The Roads and Motorways Directorate had to bear the costs not only of other emergency operations, such as safety measures in the Dölzschen rocks, but also of measures that would not have been necessary if the construction project had been properly prepared first.</seg>
<seg id="189">Expenditure of this kind includes costs related to the interruption of construction operations (€3.2 million), additional training of drilling personnel (€0.5 million) and rising wages and goods costs due to project overruns (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">The cost overruns thus amounted to around €10.7 million, which was not matched by any added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">On the basis of the lessons learned from this and other audited projects, BRH asked the Federal Ministry to apply stricter guidance in its supervision of road construction works.</seg>
<seg id="192">In doing so, the Federal Ministry should give the Road and Motorway Directorates the necessary incentive to implement quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of cooperation for BRH and SAO Cooperation fulfilled the intention of the two audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="194">BRH gained control knowledge of the preparation, assignment and progress of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">The two supreme audit institutions have built a database on the price of bridges and tunnels, which will be used for future inspections.</seg>
<seg id="196">The SAO found that the main construction-technical parameters of bridges, tunnels and the route of the D 8 motorway do not differ from those of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The auditors of both institutions involved in the cooperation have gained new experience, which they can use for further inspections.</seg>
