<p>
<seg id="1">Public works procurement and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on the parallel audit carried out by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Public procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and the private sector.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the State is to use public resources as efficiently and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor in the success of the Single Economic Area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In its legislation, the EU has set limits beyond which contracting authorities must meet certain requirements to guarantee a broad and unrestricted competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose European procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">Both the Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts that are below EU limits in value, the regulation of their award remains the responsibility of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In addition, public procurement is prone to corruption, with a consequent high potential for harm.</seg>
<seg id="12">Contracting authorities are therefore obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and unfair advantage (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI - SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI - BRH) agreed to carry out parallel inspections in the field of procurement procedures and prevention of corruption in land and transport buildings.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation was also focused on the area of European procurement law, as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">Controls included procurement below European limits to tackle the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit findings of the two supreme audit institutions are summarised in a joint report addressed, inter alia, to international organisations such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Areas of control and controlled institutions</seg>
<seg id="18">The BRH assessment is based on blanket inspections of the above mentioned areas, which were carried out with the German building authorities responsible for federal transport and land construction between 2011 and 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, the construction of motorways and large-scale building projects were evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="20">The BRH also included findings from past inspections.</seg>
<seg id="21">The SAO's assessment is based on inspections carried out between 2008 and 2012, which focused on the construction of roads, railway lines, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other buildings in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the award of federal public contracts is mostly carried out by the regional building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, public procurement in the field of transport infrastructure is the responsibility of the state institutions for road and rail construction.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the field of civil engineering, public procurement is carried out by entities receiving budget funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used at different stages of the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation should take into account the differences in public procurement legislation and the specificities of the construction market in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of the Public Procurement Act in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the conduct of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and regulations.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany are governed by budgetary law and the relevant administrative acts.</seg>
<seg id="30">The internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details on the requirements of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption are set out in the so-called federal government procurement manuals, in which the requirements are elaborated or formulated in greater detail in the light of legal precedents in the field of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legislation relating to contracts with a value above and below European limits.</seg>
<seg id="33">The procurement law underwent significant changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules have strengthened the transparency of procurement procedures, opened the way for more competition and reduced opportunities for corruption in the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="35">Fundamental aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As far as European procurement procedures are concerned, open and restricted procedures in particular need to be applied in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts below the European threshold are awarded in accordance with national rules (public call for competition, restricted call for tender, negotiated procedure), but these are practically identical to the above conditions for European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterised by the principle of preference for open procedures (where candidates are invited on a European scale) and public calls for participation (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and in the event of a call for competition, any candidate may submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is mainly achieved by dividing the total public contract into commercially specific parts and dividing it into sub-contracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">The award of contracts divided into these lots gives as many candidates as possible the opportunity to participate in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of German procurement law are time-tested tools for obtaining good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330,000 construction companies are registered in Germany, with 1.9 million employees.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, the terms of European procedures must also be applied in cases of public procurement with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception is the simplified sub-standard procedure, where the contracting authority can use less demanding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which the contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favourable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">Current Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to choose between an open procedure and a restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are 85,000 construction companies registered in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Total volume of contracting authorities' public works contracts and share of different types of procedures in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction works in Germany amounted to EUR 7 675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">Of which CZK 1,138 billion (15%) was the share of public contracts, which, in addition to contracts awarded by the federal government, included contracts awarded by individual Länder and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of federal road and land construction projects (excluding the construction of railways and waterworks) amounted to CZK 212.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of the federal contracts for land works and transport works was as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public calls; 12.7% restricted procedures and restricted calls;</seg>
<seg id="55">6.6% of negotiated procedures and direct procurement; 33.2% is the share of European procurement.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic reached CZK 118.6 billion in 2011, which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction works.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, it reached CZK 194.0 billion, which was 37% of the total volume.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of procurement types in 2011: 65.1% open procedures; 14.3% restricted procedures; 9.5% negotiated procedures; 8.4% simplified procedures for sub-standard contracts; 2.7% other procedures.</seg>
<seg id="59">These figures include all public supply, service and works contracts awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">The figures show that: Parallel checks in both countries have focused on a substantial part of public procurement procedures; prevention of corruption, which must always be taken into account in procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; open significance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and BRH carried out parallel checks on the award of European works contracts, with an emphasis on the prevention of corruption in their countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The inspections focused on comparing the legislation in both countries and the EU and on the implementation of public contracts in the field of land and transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">Key findings are set out below:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into the national laws of both countries (points 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">Preventing corruption is not only the aim of the EU directive, but of the two countries' national procurement rules, which differ in part in terms of focus and detail.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the basic requirement that tender documents must meet is to include all the information necessary for the preparation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specification shall be neutral and shall not contain any requirements restricting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">The tender documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, the problem is the lack of definition of the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, it is required to divide contracts into lots where possible in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to BRH's findings, this requirement is respected in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">The SAO's audits showed that in the Czech Republic, very large public works in the field of road construction are awarded without being divided into parts, or divided into parts, but only into very significant parts in volume. This method can distort competition and lead to restrictions on only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">Such restrictions on market potential can lead to significant cost increases and risk unserious price negotiations and abusive agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">The legislation in both countries allows contracting authorities, under certain conditions, to award additional works if the need arises after the conclusion of the contract (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">In both countries, the requirements for the correct identification of the type of procurement are met.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, according to the regulations in force, contracting entities are free to choose one of the open procurement procedures, namely an open procedure or a restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="78">German procurement and budget law enshrines the primacy of open procedures for both European and national tenders, known as public calls for competition.</seg>
<seg id="79">Open procurement procedures in both countries allow a larger pool of bidders to bid and also reduce the risk of corruption by making it more difficult to negotiate prices illegally between bidders.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best value for money results are being achieved.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of large contracts whose estimated total price reaches or exceeds the limits set by the EU, the audited contracting authorities have always launched a European procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="82">The correct determination of the estimated value of the contract plays a very important role in determining the type of procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used to objectively determine the price of public works, in which values are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is a sufficiently objective instrument.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are used only in the field of road construction, but they are not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a public works contract in accordance with European procurement procedures, it is necessary to publish prior information and a contract notice, in order to strengthen competition by allowing candidates to prepare in time for the submission of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction authorities audited completed with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, correct application of provisions and / or a lack of controls may have affected competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">There is a greater risk of manipulation in the selection of candidates to participate in a restricted procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be high enough to guarantee genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria shall be objective, non-discriminatory and published well in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition to EU requirements, contracting authorities in both countries should rotate candidates as often as possible, inviting them to participate in the procedure when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany, the requirements to prevent risks of manipulation are in part very detailed.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the audited contracting entities did not comply with these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions were not always credible (section 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting authorities must ensure that all candidates wishing to submit a tender receive the same information in the course of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreements between those interested parties and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of the specifications must, as far as possible, be prevented from restricting competition by means of unlawful agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, in several cases the German contracting authorities audited did not comply with this requirement (point 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">The requirements for labelling, documentation, protection and confidentiality of offers are designed to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">Checks in both countries found only a few cases of irregularities (section 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The assessment and evaluation of offers is regulated procedurally in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more comprehensive, but they have not always been respected by the audited contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting entities submitted their tenders to third parties for inspection without prior assessment, without properly documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">The bids were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (point 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">For reasons of legal protection, tenderers are required to be informed about the intended contract award before the latter is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection rule also is designed to prevent corrective action.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of contract award procedures also for national tenders.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in few cases, the notification of the enterprises was not adequately supported (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The tender documentation for the audited contracting authorities in both countries was not always complete or fully credible.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, the transparency requirements applied at European level were not always properly respected in the minutes of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="113">In addition, some of the weaknesses identified reduced the preventive anti-corruption function of the dossier.</seg>
<seg id="114">Contracting authorities in both countries mostly complied with their reporting obligations (point 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Summary of the guiding principles of European procurement law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">European procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure free competition in the EU, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, a Directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public works contracts, public supply contracts and public service contracts with a view to ensuring the free movement of goods and services, and a Directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to the application of review procedures to the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (the Remedies Directive), both of which were to be transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The EU's general procurement principles include, in particular: The requirement of a competitive environment; the requirement of equal treatment or non-discrimination; the requirement of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">EU procurement principles include The Directive on the coordination of public procurement procedures also includes provisions for construction projects with a total estimated value of €5 million or more.</seg>
<seg id="120">These provisions affect: The content of the tender documents; the type of procurement procedure used; the publication of certain information before, during and after the procedure; compliance with the deadline for the receipt of tenders; the qualification requirements that may be required of tenderers; the criteria for selecting the most suitable tender.</seg>
<seg id="121">The legal protection of tenderers is governed by the Remedies Directive.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of a potential breach of procurement law, tenderers may have the decisions of the contracting authority reviewed in accordance with the review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both countries have transposed EU requirements into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">The importance of preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">There is no legal definition of what corruption actually means in either country.</seg>
<seg id="127">Corruption is generally understood as an abuse of a personal (confidential) position for its own benefit.</seg>
<seg id="128">As a rule, this means that such abuse is instigated by those who benefit from it.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can be a barrier to competition and can cause serious economic losses.</seg>
<seg id="130">Total corruption-related damage is estimated to amount to 5% of global economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the EU, these costs are estimated at 1% of the EU's economic output.</seg>
<seg id="132">Where a contracting authority is involved in a contract, agreements restricting competition or allowing unfair conduct may undermine confidence in the integrity, capacity and overall work of the public administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">That is why preventing corruption is an essential task for contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">Practices and procedures must be monitored, particularly in areas particularly vulnerable to corruption, so that adequate measures can be taken to prevent corruption.</seg>
<seg id="135">Taking preventive measures and carrying out effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of the decision-making process to corruption.</seg>
