<seg id="643">If the price of the tender is significantly higher than the contracting authority's estimate, this does not justify a refusal to award the contract to the tenderer in question (unlike German procurement law).</seg>
<seg id="644">If there is a suspicion in Germany of conduct intended to restrict competition, the contracting authority is obliged to report this immediately to the competent superior authority.</seg>
<seg id="645">It must decide on the way forward and whether it is appropriate to inform the antitrust authority or the law enforcement authorities.</seg>
<seg id="646">They must also approve (e.g. if the contract exceeds €50,000 and the contract was not awarded to the lowest bidder) whether the contract will be awarded when the contract is being negotiated or whether the tender will be cancelled.</seg>
<seg id="647">The Czech rules do not regulate this area.</seg>
<seg id="648">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="649">BRH</seg>
<seg id="650">Verification of suitability and award criteria</seg>
<seg id="651">Most of the procurement procedures examined were in line with the relevant requirements.</seg>
<seg id="652">In the case of some recommendations made by self-employed potential contractors, the contracting authorities themselves did not check the suitability of the tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="653">ThissegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="654">In some procurement cases, insufficient documentation was provided as to whether all published evaluation criteria were taken into account by the contracting authority in the selection process or whether the selection decision was based solely on the price criterion.</seg>
<seg id="655">Selection of interested parties and confidentiality of tenders</seg>
<seg id="656">Some contracting authorities have used the services of unauthorised persons, such as self-employed persons or employees of building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="657">They were integrated into the planning or implementation process of construction projects, performing functions that were to be performed exclusively by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="658">Contracting authorities have tried to justify this by their lack of human resources in the sector.</seg>
<seg id="659">In some cases, they used self-employed professionals to review offers of services from people who were not formally bound to maintain the confidentiality of offers and to carry out with due care the fulfilment of their obligations under the contract.</seg>
<seg id="660">As far as contracting authorities are concerned, there was generally no conclusive evidence as to whether tenders in the custody of self-employed professionals were available only to designated persons.</seg>
<seg id="661">Review and Mathematical Control of Tenders</seg>
<seg id="662">Some contracting authorities have handed over open envelopes for further examination to self-employed professionals without first carrying out the prescribed tender examination and mathematical examination and without documenting the results of these verifications.</seg>
<seg id="663">In the event of any intention of manipulation, third parties could make changes to the tenders which could not be identified by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="664">The examination of the documents revealed a number of cases where unusual elements in the tenders were not adequately labelled or where data on prices and products were missing.</seg>
<seg id="665">Performance audits</seg>
<seg id="666">A sample check by one contracting authority revealed that in 75% of procurement cases, the most advantageous tenders deviated by more than 10% from the estimated costs.</seg>
<seg id="667">One out of 20 tenders was cancelled due to inadequate tender prices.</seg>
<seg id="668">In many cases, there was a lack of evidence or sufficient documentation on the examination of bids or negotiations with bidders for further clarification.</seg>
<seg id="669">In many cases, there was also a lack of detailed information on, for example, the unit prices of the most important invoiced items.</seg>
<seg id="670">Changes in market prices or increases in material costs were often cited as reasons for the deviations.</seg>
<seg id="671">The contracting authorities argued that it was difficult to identify and prove countervailing prices.</seg>
<seg id="672">In the case of one call for tenders, made by an entity outside the circle of normal contracting entities, a 66% lower price was offered compared to the initial cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="673">No data were recorded on the closer examination of costs or on the identification of the reasons for deviations.</seg>
<seg id="674">In clarifying this issue, the contracting authority did not find any indication of price dumping for the tenderer to whom the contract might have been awarded.</seg>
<seg id="675">It was therefore not clear whether the initial cost estimate was excessive or whether the price offered was too low.</seg>
<seg id="676">The contracting authority later rated the tenderer as a "low cost company" which was not able to meet either the quality requirements or the deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="677">In another procurement procedure, the contracting authority awarded the contract to a tenderer whose price was 35% higher than the initial cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="678">The contracting authority did not cancel the tendering procedure and put forward the unfounded argument that the tenderer could be presumed not to have based its pricing on disproportionately high costs.</seg>
<seg id="679">Suspected irregularities</seg>
<seg id="680">One contracting authority was found to have two cases of irregularities, which were reported to the firm responsible for technical supervision.</seg>
<seg id="681">In one procurement procedure, two tenderers submitted tenders containing identical price calculations, which prompted the contracting authorities to exclude both tenders.</seg>
<seg id="682">The checks did not show any significant deficiencies in the application of the other provisions.</seg>
<seg id="683">The SAO</seg>
<seg id="684">Verification of suitability</seg>
<seg id="685">For many construction projects, such as university buildings, roads and railways, contracting authorities did not exclude tenderers from participating in the procurement procedure, even though they did not meet the contracting authority's requirements set out in the terms of reference, or did not provide the required qualification, or, conversely, one contracting authority could not substantiate or explain the reason for the exclusion of a candidate who met the requirements.</seg>
<seg id="686">Evaluation</seg>
<seg id="687">In the case of the construction of a sewage treatment plant, the individual evaluation criteria of the tender for the contractor were established, but the contracting authority did not respect them during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="688">For the railway infrastructure development action, the weighting of the evaluation criteria was not set at the start of the procedure when the contract was awarded, but only at the beginning of the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="689">In the case of a road repair project, the assessment of the criterion "shortening of construction time" was not carried out correctly.</seg>
<seg id="690">For the second and third place bidders, the evaluation incorrectly indicated a greater reduction in the construction time than indicated in their bids.</seg>
<seg id="691">Documentation of the reasons for selecting a candidate</seg>
<seg id="692">For the three actions related to housing promotion, the contracting authority did not provide evidence on the basis of which criteria it assessed the tenders received and how it selected the most suitable of them.</seg>
<seg id="693">Accuracy of the selection of suppliers of small scale contracts related to the construction of a road circuit with an estimated price of up to 500 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="694">It was not possible to verify CZK, as suppliers were selected only on the basis of telephone consultations about the price and the date of performance, but documents about these negotiations were not prepared.</seg>
<seg id="695">Summary</seg>
<seg id="696">In both countries, the rules for the verification and evaluation of offers are in line with EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, they differ with regard to the specific steps of the procedure and the choice of individuals involved in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="698">In Germany, unlike the Czech Republic, these steps in the procurement process are governed by stricter and more detailed requirements, especially as regards the application of the cross principle and the protection of bids.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the rules for verifying the appropriateness of the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, it was found in some cases that the essential steps of the process in the verification and evaluation of tenders were not documented at all and, if so, only partially.</seg>
<seg id="701">The lack of control tools and transparency in the decision-making process during the review and evaluation of bids allows manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="702">Inspections have shown serious deficiencies, such as the transmission of tenders to third parties without prior appropriate verification and documentation of tenders by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="703">Where contracting entities entrust a third party with the performance of functions related to the examination and evaluation of tenders, appropriate measures and increased control of measures against the increased possibility of manipulation shall be necessary.</seg>
<seg id="704">In all cases, the German contracting authorities audited did not use the full set of available tools to check the validity of prices and did not deal with their own price structure.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, shortcomings were found in the evaluation of the appropriateness of the offers and the use of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Completion of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="707">After examination and evaluation of the tenders, the procurement process is completed by the award of the contract or the cancellation of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">Requirements of European law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In the case of a European procedure, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the decision to award the contract.</seg>
<seg id="710">Suppliers shall have the opportunity to review the decision taken within a limited period of 10 or 15 days and to request a review if appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="711">ThissegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="712">The time limit of 10 days applies to electronic submissions and 15 days to other submissions.</seg>
<seg id="713">The contract may not be concluded before the expiry of this period or before the decision of the review procedure.</seg>
<seg id="714">If the review body rejects the complaint and upholds the decision, candidates and tenderers must be given the opportunity to have the correctness of the application of the procurement law reviewed by an independent court.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting authority will be able to circumvent the legal protection of suppliers by swiftly implementing procurement decisions.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting authority shall document the progress of the procedure in an appropriate manner.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries have implemented management information obligations.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure rests with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, it cannot arbitrarily deviate from the results of a properly conducted examination and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority is to conclude the contract within a specified period.</seg>
<seg id="723">This is due to the fact that the tenderer is not bound by its tender after the expiry of this period.</seg>
<seg id="724">The content of the contract must not deviate from the winning bid.</seg>
<seg id="725">Unsuccessful tenderers should be informed of the result in good time, stating the reason why their bid was not accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">The cancellation of a procurement procedure is only allowed if certain conditions are met, for example if the prices in the tenders do not meet the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory waiting time before the conclusion of a contract of 10 or 15 days applies to both European and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, the equivalent provision applies only to European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other procedures in Germany, tenderers cannot be informed of the award of a contract before a decision on its EU provisions and review award.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, the tender procedure must be cancelled if only one tender was received or if only one tender met the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, a contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that the tender meets the conditions set out in the tender documents and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">The checks found few irregularities in the completion of the audited procurement processes.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some European cases, proxy companies have received letters before the notification deadline, which can invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also in several cases of open procedures, the letters of authorisation contained modifications incompatible with the content of the tender, such as new deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, contracting authorities did not meet the deadlines for awarding the contract.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous tender because the tenderer offering a price more than 50% lower no longer wished to fulfil the contract at the price originally offered.</seg>
<seg id="740">The SAO</seg>
<seg id="741">In one case, during the reconstruction and construction of the university, the contracting authority did not conclude a contract with the contractor for the work in accordance with the draft contract contained in the tender of the selected tenderer.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some road repair and maintenance operations, the construction of a motorway and a road ring road, contracts were concluded later than stipulated by law.</seg>
<seg id="743">In the case of construction works in former military tours, the contracting authority sent a notice of the selection of the most suitable tender to all tenderers only after the legal deadline.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented EU rules on the termination of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="746">The legal protection of unsuccessful candidates helps to reduce corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Act includes an institute of legal protection even in cases of contracts below EU limits.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, it was found that the limited time limit for concluding the contract was exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can cause adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, contracting authorities should eliminate such deficiencies in the conclusion of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notification, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process, with all its different stages, relevant findings and decisions, including the relevant justifications, shall be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">The completion of the procurement procedure at European level must be made public.</seg>
<seg id="754">Data on procurement procedures are summarised in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of European law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document procurement procedures is in line with the fundamental requirement of the principle of transparency, which applies at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only proper and time-relevant documentation of decision-making and justification guarantees transparency in the procurement process and, above all, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each tenderer in cases where the value of the contract exceeds European limits.</seg>
<seg id="758">Adequate documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, as the obligation to provide detailed reasons for individual decisions and their merits significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In European procurement cases, the contracting authority must notify the EU's Office of Official Publications within 48 days of the date of award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Authority publishes the notification in the Official Journal of the EU, which also meets the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarise the essential information on its procurement procedures and communicate it to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission publishes annual statistics which provide an overview of the development of the single market in the field of construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed the provisions of the European law on documentation and notification obligations into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for European statistics are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to notify the award of a contract applies not only to European procedures, but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notification period is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those that are mandatory under European law, applies only to limited procedures exceeding the limit of €25,000 ($625,000) and direct procedures exceeding the limit of €15,000 ($375,000), including VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Only interested parties shall be informed below this limit.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of entries have not been fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, such as the reasons for the supply specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of one procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it had concluded a contract with a tenderer whose tender did not contain the mandatory requirements.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases some of the required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Publication of the contract award</seg>
<seg id="780">In the case of some European procedures, the contracting authority erred in the publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In the case of several awards, there was no evidence of publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="782">Obligation to notify</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistically proven files included the required minimum of information and were created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Preliminary transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority has published information on the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting authority, information about the contract was not published due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the sponsor six months to notice the error.</seg>
<seg id="788">As a result, the outcome of the proceedings was not made public during that period.</seg>
<seg id="789">The SAO</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">For events related to the organisation of a major sporting event, significant deficiencies were found in the tender documentation, such as incorrect tender price data in the minutes of the evaluation committee meeting.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some of the opening documents were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Publication of the contract award</seg>
<seg id="794">In preparation for repairs and maintenance of roads, construction of the motorway and the road circuit, the contract award notices were sent after the deadline or were not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">The provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations cover European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures the transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">The Czech reporting obligations are somewhat stricter compared to the German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The checks revealed shortcomings that significantly reduced the value of documentation as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">ThissegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to enhance the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with the notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary assessment and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits of the SAO and BRH focused on two areas that are essential for the public procurement process in both the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation provides an opportunity for international competition within the EU with a view to creating a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Measures to prevent corruption are not only aimed at avoiding or at least reducing corruption, but also at preventing financial damage and possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two audit institutions - the SAO and BRH - with regard to the application of the procurement law of the two countries and the comparison of its relevant provisions give an internal view of the common and different elements that can help both countries in the further development and application of this law.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed EU public procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">In both countries, there is thus an important common basis for public procurement and the fulfilment of the basic requirements in the area of: Competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting authorities reinforce these requirements in part through very extensive measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has extended the provisions on public procurement requiring European procedures to procedures that are below EU limits and are therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, inspections have shown that contracting authorities do not always fully comply with all relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate these irregularities, taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, checks have identified risks affecting economy and value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">These include, in particular, the incomplete definition of the subject-matter of the contract, which resulted in additional works, which were often awarded in breach of the law, the lack of definition of the expected price, and the required qualifications, which narrowed the potential pool of bidders and thus reduced competition, especially in the field of transport works.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The joint checks were not intended to detect cases of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that both BRH and the SAO did not have sufficient tools to do so.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they can examine whether the competent authorities of both countries are taking measures to reduce corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">When it comes to preventing corruption, the two countries have focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">In particular, the German provisions provide for broad and unrestricted competition, transparency and controls as a central element in preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">In particular, the Czech regulations aim at strengthening the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, there are general principles for preventing corruption that apply to the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles have also been incorporated into public procurement requirements and have been adopted to meet the specific needs of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, sometimes with great precision, how to meet the requirements for preventing corruption during the procurement procedure and for selecting the persons involved in it.</seg>
<seg id="827">In BRH's view, the principle of preference for open procurement procedures and calls for participation is a particularly appropriate instrument to substantially reduce the risk of corruption in public procurement, while limiting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate controls (in particular the principle of cross-checking), transparency requirements, tender documentation and various organisational measures are also effective mechanisms to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">BRH therefore does not feel the need for substantial changes to the current provisions that public institutions have to comply with when awarding public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The discrepancies found in some areas highlighted weaknesses in compliance with some requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting authorities should provide further training to their staff, familiarising them with anti-corruption requirements and further raising their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the weaknesses identified relate to activities delegated by the building administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the lack of adequate controls on the delegation of powers increases the risk of misuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Activities susceptible to manipulation and corruption should therefore be transferred to third parties only if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against unauthorised interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">The SAO</seg>
<seg id="837">Anti-corruption strategies have been adopted at government level in the Czech Republic, which also have a significant impact on public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="838">The SAO's audit activities took place during a period when one of the most important parts of this strategy was implemented, namely a significant change in the Public Procurement Act and the adoption of subsequent implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The strategy adopted and the new legislation can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">For example, under the new regulations, the contracting authority must justify the effectiveness of the public contract, the determination of the estimated value of the public contract, the adequacy of the requirements for qualifications, the establishment of basic evaluation criteria and the way tenders are evaluated, and properly document and publish everything.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, both the SAO and the BRH have a favourable opinion of the ways in which the EU requirements are implemented.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their wide application in practice has confirmed that the EU's requirements for competition, equal treatment and transparency provide an appropriate basis for public procurement within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model, established in the EU, can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the great potential for material and intangible damage resulting from manipulation and corruption in connection with public procurement, both BRH and the SAO insist that it is the responsibility of contracting authorities to continue measures against corruption and manipulation and to improve them where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, organisational structures and procurement processes should be continuously monitored for weaknesses and risks in order to identify and respond appropriately to the need for corrective action.</seg>
<seg id="847">Compared to the practice in Germany, it appeared that the share of open tender procedures in the Czech Republic, which give room to competition and substantially reduce the possibility of corrupt behaviour, should increase.</seg>
<seg id="848">The award of contracts in parts can also have a positive impact on the price achieved in cases where it is permissible and appropriate for the contracting authority. A higher number of bidders puts pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">The organisation of the procurement procedure also has an impact on the conduct of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, it is provided by special state organisations, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport structures, it is organised by the central authorities themselves or through contractual organisations.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both the SAO and BRH wish to further develop knowledge in their work where it is appropriate, and to address it with their parliament and government beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">In addition, they believe that the principles of procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), as these principles and findings are of general importance for the effective fight against corruption and for ensuring that public contracts are awarded under a regime of well-functioning and fair competition and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="853">Attachments</seg>
</p>
