<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_15_33" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="OPPO">
<p>
<seg id="1">Joint FINAL REPORT on the results of parallel checks on the administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint Final Report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="7">The present joint report reports on the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic, focusing on the administration of excise duties in 2012-2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">Cooperation between the highest audit institutions of both countries was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the SAO of the Slovak Republic and the SAO of the Czech Republic in the performance of parallel audits focused on the administration of excise duties, which was concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The topic of parallel checks was chosen on the basis of the fact that the two EU Member States are based on common European legislation in order to find out how it is applied at national level, how the excise tax administration system is set up and how the systems in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic are different.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefits of the control actions carried out were the exchange of experience, identification of differences and identification of good practice.</seg>
<seg id="11">Last but not least, it was beneficial to note that the international comparability of data on the performance and efficiency of excise administration is very limited without parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala,</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrik,</seg>
<seg id="14">The President</seg>
<seg id="15">The President</seg>
<seg id="16">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">On the results of parallel inspections of the SPD administration in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The regulation of excise duties in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and their administration is in line with EU legislation and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences have been found between the adjustment of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic; in the Czech Republic, verification of the economic stability of applicants for permits and mandatory marking and colouring of selected mineral oils and certain other oils contribute to the effective administration of excise duties; in the Slovak Republic, the distribution of control stamps is easier than in the Czech Republic and less burdensome for tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against evasion of excise duties, the supervision of the movement of raw tobacco or tobacco raw material, the implementation of the institute of fuel distributors and the registration of sellers of consumer packaging of alcohol have proven to be good practice in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="23">Revenues from excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic are growing more slowly than other tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="24">The EU's goals of reducing taxes on labour, introducing eco-saving measures and reducing dependence on tobacco and alcohol have not yet been met in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, not least because indexation of excise duty rates is not introduced in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This has the effect of reducing the importance of excise duties on overall tax revenue and, as a result of increasing purchasing power, reducing the tax burden on consumption taxes in real terms.</seg>
<seg id="26">The introduction of environmental measures has long been financially supported by the state, but these measures have a negative impact on revenues from excise duties, which in the future will have to be replaced by other revenues or a reduction in state expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative expenses incurred in administering excise duties in both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic have been increasing over the long term, mainly due to wage increases, and their efficiency is decreasing.</seg>
<seg id="28">In the Slovak Republic, this efficiency is also negatively affected by expenditure on the computerisation of the administration of excise duties (IT expenditure) and expenditure on the salaries of employees performing permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses for alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="29">The computerisation of excise administration in the Slovak Republic has not had a significant impact on the reduction in the number of tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="30">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend that the Slovak Ministry reassess the validity of the exercise of permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses for ethyl alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the efficiency of administrative expenditure was influenced by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures during the audited period that would have led to a reduction in the personnel requirements of the excise administration.</seg>
