<seg id="826">- Since the carrier was instructed by a Danish entrepreneur (EDK) and the transport was carried out under his name, at his risk and on his own account, the delivery of the German subcontractor (eD) took place where the transport started - in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="827">Although the wind farms were shipped to another Member State and the recipient is a registered payer from another Member State, the supply of a German subcontractor (eD) could not be exempted because another Member State of destination is different from another Member State of the registered office of the Czech company.</seg>
<seg id="828">This supply is therefore correctly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (ECZ) deducted the input tax in its tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="829">The place of delivery to the Czech company (ECR) is also determined by the beginning of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="830">The transport of some wind power plants started in the Czech Republic and others in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="831">- The delivery of those wind power plants that are produced in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="832">- The supply of other wind farms that are produced in Germany took place in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="833">Thus, the Czech company (ECR) carried out both intra-community delivery from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-community delivery from Germany to Austria.</seg>
<seg id="834">BRH found that the Czech company (ECR) did not declare any intra-Community acquisitions in its VAT return in Germany, nor did it submit SH to the German CLO.</seg>
<seg id="835">So it is possible that the Czech company reported all intra-community deliveries uniformly as intra-community deliveries from the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="836">The SAO found that (ECR) did not report any intra-community deliveries to Austria, but intra-community deliveries to Denmark.</seg>
<seg id="837">An examination of the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria would require the cooperation of at least four tax administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German), even though this case does not show any sign of tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="838">In addition, the SAO and BRH examined the transactions to point out the differences between the declaration in the tax return and the VIES data, which were due to the different VAT legislation in 2004.</seg>
<seg id="839">The audited cases also demonstrate that changes in the legislation need time for the implementation of the new legislation by both payers and tax authorities:</seg>
<seg id="840">In the SH for the second to fourth quarters of 2004, the Czech payer reported intra-community supplies to the German payer for a total value of 792 977 452 CZK (25 197 885 EUR).</seg>
<seg id="841">During the same period, another Czech payer in SH reported an intra-community delivery to another German payer for a total value of 18,157,265 CZK (576,970 EUR).</seg>
<seg id="842">According to the information provided by the SAO from BRH, both cases involved the supply of electricity.</seg>
<seg id="843">Both Czech payers listed the above supplies in the SH in accordance with the text of Act No 235 / 2004 Coll., which was in force in 2004.</seg>
<seg id="844">By further examining the above transactions, a group of auditors of the SAO found that in 2004 there were differences between the Czech Republic and Germany in the legal arrangements for the supply or purchase of electricity.</seg>
<seg id="845">While in the Czech Republic the payers reported the supply of electricity in accordance with the current version of Act No 235 / 2004 Coll. as an intra-community supply of goods, from the point of view of the German legislation in force in 2004, it was not an intra-community acquisition, but a taxable transaction with the place of performance of the transaction in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="846">The difference in legal regulations was eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Act No. 635 / 2004 Coll., which amends certain laws in connection with the adoption of the Act on Administrative Fees, effective from 1 January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="847">In addition, when examining selected intra-community transactions in cooperation with BRH, it was found that the Czech payer reported in SH for the 1st to 4th quarters of 2005 intra-community delivery to the German payer for a total value of 240,411,163 CZK (8,071,823 EUR) and another Czech payer reported in SH for the same period intra-community delivery to the German payer for a total value of 263,470,776 CZK (8,846,050 EUR).</seg>
<seg id="848">According to the information provided by the SAO from BRH, both cases involved the supply of electricity.</seg>
<seg id="849">According to the wording of Act No 235 / 2004 Coll., effective from 1 January 2005, in the case of the supply of electricity, the place of supply is the place where the customer has his registered office, place of business or where he has an establishment for which the goods are supplied.</seg>
<seg id="850">Therefore, Czech payers should not have declared the supply of electricity to SH in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="851">The fact that the two payers mentioned above reported the intra-Community supply of electricity in SH distorted the data in VIES by a total of 503,881,939 CZK (16,917,873 EUR).</seg>
<seg id="852">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="853">The cooperation met the objectives of BRH and the SAO.</seg>
<seg id="854">Both SAIs have acquired a deeper knowledge of the VAT administration systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="855">The cooperation revealed the differences between the two systems and showed that the legislation on VAT management differs.</seg>
<seg id="856">During parallel checks, suspicious cases of intra-community transactions were identified.</seg>
<seg id="857">It makes sense to examine some of them afterwards.</seg>
<seg id="858">On the basis of the audit findings, both SAIs made recommendations on VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="859">The follow-up of these recommendations should also be part of the follow-up.</seg>
<seg id="860">The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of the two audit institutions is the basis for the successful implementation of the following controls on the VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="861">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="862">The report was written in Czech, English and German and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the President of the Bundesrechnungshof, the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
</p>
