<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in the control of excise administration between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted joint report reports on the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky, focused on the administration of excise duties in the period after the accession of the two countries to the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation was carried out on the basis of a contract for cooperation in control activities concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel checks was chosen in the light of a fundamental change in the system of collection of excise duties, which took place in connection with the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union from 1 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the internal market of the European Union requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow goods not subject to tax to circulate until the date of their delivery for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with that principle, the new legislation adopted in both countries allows the movement of goods under tax supervision under a suspensive regime.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great demands on the tax authorities and requires close cooperation between the competent administrative authorities of the Member States in the fight against tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation on controls of the administration of excise duties for the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (Czech Republic) 05 / 34 (SR) 48 / 11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of inspection: (Czech Republic) Administration of Excise Duties (Slovak Republic) Procedure of the collegiate authorities in the administration of spotreble taxes</seg>
<seg id="14">On 8 February 2006, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter "NKÚ-ČR") and the Najvyššší kontrolný úrad Slovenskej republiky (hereinafter "SAO SR") concluded a "Treaty on Cooperation in Audit Activities."</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel inspections of the "Administration of Excise Taxes," included in the NKÚ-ČR audit activity plan for 2005 under No 05 / 34, and "Control of the procedure of the collegiate authorities in the administration of spotreble taxes," included in the audit activity plan of the SAO SR for 2006 under No 48 / 11.</seg>
<seg id="16">The parallel checks had the character of coordinated checks.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information that the contracting parties could not obtain during the inspection of the administration of excise duties on the territory of their state and in the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the inspections within the meaning of the European implementing directives for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards - Directive No 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">In the territory of the Czech Republic, the inspection (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic") was carried out by groups of auditors from the State Budget Department and from the territorial departments of Central Bohemia, South Bohemia, West Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, Northeast Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and Northern Moravia between 7 February and 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">27 inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="20">The audited entities were the Directorate-General for Customs (hereinafter referred to as "the GSC") and 11 tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the framework of the GŘC, 12 selected customs offices out of a total of 54 were inspected.</seg>
<seg id="22">The audit on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "SR") was carried out by the financial and tax section of the SAO SR in cooperation with the expositions of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 5 customs offices out of a total of 9 in the period from 13 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">Eight inspectors were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of the parallel checks was to examine the customs authorities' handling of excise duties and compliance with the relevant legislation in force in both countries and in the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">International cooperation focused on the procedure of tax authorities in the exercise of supervision over the transport of goods subject to excise duties, in particular on the registration of initiated and completed shipments under the conditional exemption regime, and on the exchange of information in the framework of mutual administrative assistance between excise tax authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="27">The administration of excise duties in the Czech Republic was carried out by the tax authorities until 31 December 2003.</seg>
<seg id="28">Since 1 January 2004, this agenda has been taken over by the customs authorities, which have so far only collected excise duty on imports.</seg>
<seg id="29">In the Czech Republic, mineral oils, alcohol, beer, wine and intermediate products and tobacco products are subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="30">The revenue of the state budget from excise duties in the Czech Republic amounted to a total of CZK 82.8 billion in 2004 and excise duties accounted for 19.5% of the revenue of the state budget from taxes and fees amounting to CZK 424.7 billion.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005, the revenue of the state budget from excise duties amounted to CZK 103.6 billion and the share of the state budget revenue from taxes and fees of CZK 460.4 billion was 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the revenue from excise duty on mineral oils to the state budget amounted to 80% of the total revenue from this tax and in 2005 it amounted to 90.9%.</seg>
<seg id="33">The difference from 100% in the amount of CZK 13 billion in 2004 and CZK 6.9 billion in 2005 was the income of the State Fund for Transport Infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="34">The administration of all excise duties in the Slovak Republic has been carried out by the customs authorities since 1 May 2004, with the exception of excise duty on mineral oil, the administration of which has been carried out since 1 January 2002.</seg>
<seg id="35">Until then, excise duties had been administered by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="36">Mineral oil, alcohol, beer, wine and tobacco products are subject to excise duty in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="37">The revenue of the state budget from excise duties in the Slovak Republic amounted to a total of Sk 43.4 billion in 2004 and excise duties accounted for 20.7% of the total tax revenue of Sk 209.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="38">In 2005, the state budget revenue from excise duties was CZK 50 billion and excise duties accounted for 22.5% of the total tax revenue of CZK 222.6 billion.</seg>
<seg id="39">Chart 1 - Comparison of revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic from taxes and fees and tax revenues of the state budget of the Slovak Republic with revenues from excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="40">- Council Directive 92 / 12 / EEC on the general arrangements for products subject to excise duty and on the holding, movement and monitoring of such products ("Directive 92 / 12 / EEC"), - Council Regulation (EC) No 2073 / 2004 on administrative cooperation in the field of excise duties ("Regulation No 2073 / 2004"), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 2719 / 92 on the accompanying official document for the movement of products subject to excise duty under suspension of excise duty ("Regulation No 2719 / 92"), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 3649 / 92 on a simplified accompanying document for the movement within the Community of products subject to excise duty which have been released for consumption in the Member State of dispatch ("Regulation No 3649 / 92").</seg>
<seg id="41">The basic legislation governing the issue of excise duties in the Czech Republic is Act No 353 / 2003 Coll., on Excise Duties, as amended, (hereinafter "Act No 353 / 2003 Coll."), which took effect from 1 January 2004.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic, the customs authorities are, inter alia, bound by the following generally binding legislation: - Act No 98 / 2004 Z. Z. on the Spotrebnej Tax on Mineral Oil in the Zneší predpisov (hereinafter "Act No 98 / 2004 Z. z."), - Act No 104 / 2004 Z. on the Spotrebnej Tax on Wine in the Zneší predpisov (hereinafter "Act No 104 / 2004 Z. z."), - Act No 105 / 2004 Z. Z. on the Spotrebnej Tax on Lieh in the Zneší predpisov (hereinafter "Act No 105 / 2004 Z. z."), - Act No 106 / 2004 Z. on the Spotrebnej Tax on Tabak Products in the Zneší predpisov (hereinafter "Act No 106 / 2004 Z. z."), - Act No 107 / 2004 Z. Z. on the Spotrebnej Tax on Beer in the Zneh predpisov (hereinafter "Act No 107 / 2004 Z. z.").</seg>
<seg id="43">2.1 Movement of excise goods under suspension of duty between Member States of the EU</seg>
<seg id="44">The conditions governing the movement of excise goods under suspension of duty are governed by Directive 92 / 12 / EEC, in Title III - Movement of goods, Articles 15 to 20.</seg>
<seg id="45">Under those provisions, the transport of those goods may be carried out only by an authorised warehousekeeper, who means a natural or legal person authorised by the competent authorities of a Member State to manufacture, process, store, receive and dispatch products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="46">The consignee in another Member State may be an authorised warehousekeeper or an economic operator without the status of authorised warehousekeeper, who may not, however, store or dispatch such products under a suspensive arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="47">Authorised warehousekeeper in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic means the operator of a tax warehouse, the economic operator is the authorised recipient for the repeated or one-off receipt of products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="48">The movement of products subject to excise duty under suspension of duty is only possible under Directive 92 / 12 / EEC with an accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="49">The accompanying document shall be drawn up by the consignor in four copies before the start of the journey, unless further copies are required by the competent authorities of the Member State of dispatch.</seg>
<seg id="50">2.2 Procedure for starting and ending the transport of goods under the conditional exemption regime between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="51">Transport from the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="52">The procedure for starting transport is governed by the provisions of Section 25 (3) of Act No 353 / 2003 Coll., which states, among other things:</seg>
<seg id="53">"The operator of the tax warehouse shall inform the customs office, which is the local competent tax warehouse from which the transport is to begin, before the transport of the selected products begins;</seg>
<seg id="54">The transport of the selected products can only start with the approval of this customs office.</seg>
<seg id="55">The customs office shall give its consent to the transport of the selected products without delay after the condition of securing the tax has been met... "</seg>
<seg id="56">The consignor in the Czech Republic can start the transport of all types of products subject to excise duty only with the consent of the locally competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="57">The customs office will only give its consent to the start of transport if security is provided for the amount of tax due on the goods transported.</seg>
<seg id="58">The consignor is required to draw up the accompanying document in five copies before the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="59">The customs office shall indicate on the accompanying document its agreement to the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="60">Copy No 1 shall be kept by the consignor, copy No 2, 3 and copy No 4 shall be handed over by the consignor to the carrier and copy No 5 shall be kept by the customs office authorising the transport.</seg>
<seg id="61">Under Slovak law, the consignee in SR keeps copy No 2 of the accompanying document. On copies No 3 and 4, he confirms receipt of the products and submits both copies to the local competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="62">Copy No 3, certified by the customs office, shall be sent to the consignor no later than the 15th day of the month following the calendar month in which he received the products.</seg>
<seg id="63">Copy No 4 shall be kept by the customs office of the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="64">The transport is terminated by the acceptance of the products by the recipient.</seg>
<seg id="65">The release of the security of the tax will be decided by the customs office in the Czech Republic, which authorised the start of the transport, within 5 working days of the presentation of copy No 3 of the accompanying document, which is confirmed by the consignee and the Slovak customs office.</seg>
<seg id="66">Chart 2 - Circulation of the accompanying document for transport started in the Czech Republic and ended in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="67">Transport from Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="68">Until 31 December 2005, the procedure for transporting alcohol and tobacco products from Slovakia to another Member State of the European Union was amended as follows:</seg>
<seg id="69">Pursuant to Article 26 (4) of Law No 105 / 2004 Z. z.</seg>
<seg id="70">"When transporting lieh from a tax warehouse in the tax territory to a tax warehouse, or to an authorised recipient, or to a tax beneficiary in an inom member's staff, the odosielatel" (the supplier ") is obliged to send the copy of the first diel of the preparatory document electronically or faxom to the Poprad Colný úrad on the day of the start of the transport; this copy is also required to be sent to the colný úrad by writing to the piatich of working days from the day of the start of the transport."</seg>
<seg id="71">Pursuant to Article 22 (4) of Law No 106 / 2004 Z. z.</seg>
<seg id="72">"When transporting tobacco products from a tax warehouse in the tax territory to a tax warehouse, or to an authorised recipient, or to a tax beneficiary in an inom member's staff, the odosielatel" (the supplier ") is obliged to send the code of the first diel of the sprievodní document electronically or fax to the Colný úrad Poprad on the day of the start of the transport; this code is also required to be sent to the colný úrad písomne najneskor in the piatich working days from the day of the start of the transport."</seg>
<seg id="73">For the transport of other products subject to excise duty (mineral oil, wine and beer) during the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 ("the audited period"), the taxpayer was not obliged to notify the Poprad Customs Office or the competent customs office of the start of the transport under suspension of duty.</seg>
<seg id="74">The tax authority only became aware of the transport of these products during a local investigation or during a tax inspection from the accompanying documents and the accounting documents of the tax entity.</seg>
<seg id="75">The consignor in SR is obliged to draw up the accompanying document in four copies before the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="76">Copy No 1 shall be retained by the consignor (when transporting ethyl alcohol and tobacco products, he shall send a copy of copy No 1 electronically or by fax to the Poprad customs office and the competent customs office).</seg>
<seg id="77">Copies Nos 2, 3 and 4 shall accompany the goods being transported.</seg>
<seg id="78">According to the Czech legislation, the consignee in the Czech Republic keeps copy No 2 of the accompanying document issued by the consignor in the Slovak Republic and confirms receipt of the products on copies No 3 and 4.</seg>
<seg id="79">Certified copies Nos 3 and 4 will be sent no later than the first working day after the end of the transport to the local customs office in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="80">Copy No 4 shall be retained by the customs office and copy No 3 shall be returned to the consignee to verify its accuracy and validity.</seg>
<seg id="81">The consignee shall send the certified copy No 3 no later than the following working day after receipt to the consignor in SR.</seg>
<seg id="82">Transport in the Slovak Republic is considered to have ended on the date of receipt of the products by the recipient.</seg>
<seg id="83">The consignor proves the termination of the transport by producing copy No 3 of the accompanying document certified by the consignee and the tax authority in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="84">Figure 3 - Circulation of the accompanying document for transport (alcohol and tobacco products) started in Slovakia and ended in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="85">In 2006, amendments to all laws on excise duties were gradually adopted in the Slovak Republic, according to which the consignor of goods under the conditional exemption procedure is obliged to send a copy of copy No 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office of the locally competent consignor before the start of transport.</seg>
<seg id="86">The document proving the end of the transport of alcohol and tobacco products shall be copy No 3 of the accompanying document, certified by the consignee and his competent tax authority.</seg>
<seg id="87">The document proving that the transport of mineral oils, wine and beer has ended is copy No 3, certified by the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="88">Confirmation by the tax authorities of another Member State that the goods have been taken over by the consignee shall be required if the latter is required, under the legislation of the Member State concerned, to certify copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="89">2.3 Registry of initiated and completed shipments conducted by customs authorities in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="90">A single electronic system is not in place to monitor the movement of goods under suspension of duty between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="91">Decision 1152 / 2003 / EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 on the introduction of an electronic system for the transport and monitoring of products subject to excise duty requires Member States and the European Commission to introduce, from 1 July 2009, an electronic system (Excise Movement and Control System) to enable excise authorities in each Member State to obtain real-time information on the movement of goods.</seg>
<seg id="92">The system will allow the electronic transmission of accompanying documents, which are currently only used in paper form, and will contribute to simplifying the movement of goods under the conditional exemption regime and to ensuring more effective control of the movement of untaxed products across all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="93">This system will include the national transport databases of the Member States.</seg>
<seg id="94">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic records all transport started and finished on the territory of the Czech Republic in the module Evidence of Selected Products ("EVV").</seg>
<seg id="95">All customs authorities in the Czech Republic have online access to the system.</seg>
<seg id="96">In the case of shipments carried out only on the territory of the Czech Republic, the tax authorities can obtain information about the start or end of the transport immediately after the registration of the accompanying document by the customs office in EVV.</seg>
<seg id="97">The customs office shall release the security of the tax on the products transported provided by the consignor at the time of registration of the end of the transport by the customs office to the consignee responsible for the place.</seg>
<seg id="98">Customs offices in the Slovak Republic use a database based on SysNed application software, which ensures the automation of their activities in the administration of excise duties and communication with European Union systems.</seg>
<seg id="99">By registering a tax warehouse, tax warehouse operator or authorised recipient in SysNed's application software, this information is automatically transferred to the "System for Exchange of Excise Data" ("SEED") database.</seg>
<seg id="100">3. Preparation and progress of cooperation</seg>
<seg id="101">The first coordination meeting between representatives of the NKÚ-ČR and representatives of the SAO SR, at which the specific procedure for cooperation in the implementation of parallel controls in the field of excise duties was discussed, took place in January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="102">The two sides got to know each other about the excise legislation and the organisation of the excise administration in both states.</seg>
<seg id="103">Special attention was paid to the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in authorising, respectively, the initiation and termination of the transport of products subject to excise duty under the conditional exemption regime and the exchange of information between the excise authorities of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">At the meeting, it was agreed that the Czech and Slovak sides would: - process the total data on the quantities of products subject to excise duty transported from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic and vice versa, the transport of which started during the audited period, - compare the data on the transport of mineral oils - Combined Nomenclature codes 2710 and 2711 and ethyl alcohol - Combined Nomenclature codes 2207 and 2208 under the suspension regime started in the Czech Republic and ended in the Slovak Republic and vice versa in November 2004 and September 2005.</seg>
<seg id="105">In the course of the checks, the periods examined were extended to include the months of October and November 2005, and the transport of tobacco products under the conditional exemption scheme was also subject to checks during those months.</seg>
<seg id="106">Tables 1 and 2 show the total quantity of products subject to excise duty which were transported under the suspension arrangement between Czech and Slovak tax entities during the audited period.</seg>
<seg id="107">4. Comparison of records of shipments of goods under suspension of duty</seg>
<seg id="108">The NKÚ-ČR handed over to the Slovak side a database of shipments completed in the Czech Republic, which contained a total of 5,876 items listed on accompanying documents, of which 5,738 items related to mineral oils, 134 items of alcohol and 4 items of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="109">The SAO SR handed over to the Czech side a database of shipments completed in the Slovak Republic, which contained a total of 3,319 items listed on accompanying documents, of which 696 items related to mineral oil, 2,066 items of alcohol and 557 items of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="110">The NKÚ-ČR compared the data on shipments listed in the register of started shipments in the Czech Republic with the data on completed shipments registered in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="111">The results of the comparison are presented in Table 3.</seg>
<seg id="112">Data on shipments in the months of November 2004 and September 2005 were compared by the NKÚ-ČR with the database of the Slovak customs administration, which was handed over to it by the SAO SR at the beginning of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="113">The database did not contain data that could reliably agree individual traffic, and therefore only 63% of the traffic started could be attributed.</seg>
<seg id="114">Individual shipments were assigned according to multiple data, e.g. sender, consignee, date of transport, quantity of products transported.</seg>
<seg id="115">Data on shipments started in the Czech Republic and completed in the Slovak Republic in the months of October and November 2005 were compared by the NKÚ-ČR with a database of the Slovak customs administration, which contained all data according to accompanying documents, on the basis of which it was possible to clearly assign 93% of the shipments started.</seg>
<seg id="116">In the database of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, data on the quantity of mineral oils were given in litres or tonnes, depending on the type of mineral oil.</seg>
<seg id="117">In most cases, the quantity of alcohol was expressed in litres, which could, however, be converted into litres of absolute alcohol on the basis of the percentage of alcohol in the database.</seg>
<seg id="118">The quantity of tobacco products was given in pieces, in thousands of pieces and kilograms by type of tobacco product.</seg>
<seg id="119">For shipments initiated in the Czech Republic, the completion of which could not be reliably verified in the Slovak database or for which the quantity of products transported did not match, the accompanying documents were checked.</seg>
<seg id="120">Documents accompanying 487 shipments of alcohol, mineral oils and tobacco products were checked.</seg>
<seg id="121">The inspection of these documents was carried out at the customs offices where the NKÚ-ČR carried out the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="122">For shipments authorised by other customs offices, the accompanying documents were requested through the GŘC.</seg>
<seg id="123">The Czech side asked the Slovak side to verify the implementation of 141 shipments, for which the customs authorities in the Czech Republic did not provide certified copies No 3 of the accompanying document, or the quantity of products listed on the accompanying document did not agree with the quantity of products listed in the database.</seg>
<seg id="124">In addition, data on shipments registered in the Slovak database were transmitted to the Slovak side, which, however, was not included in the database of shipments of the Czech customs administration.</seg>
<seg id="125">The SAO SR found 95 shipments in the database of the Slovak Customs Administration.</seg>
<seg id="126">He requested verification of the remaining 46 shipments from the local customs authorities, which proved their completion with copies of the accompanying documents.</seg>
<seg id="127">The Slovak side forwarded to the Czech side copies of the accompanying documents, on the basis of which the transport was also identified in the Czech database, with the exception of the transport carried out by two Czech tax entities, which were not found in the Czech database of started transport.</seg>
<seg id="128">An examination of these cases revealed:</seg>
<seg id="129">- The Slovak transport database registered 11 shipments of alcohol in a total quantity of 276.7 litres of alcohol carried out by the Czech tax entity in 2004 and 20 shipments of alcohol in a total quantity of 404.66 litres of alcohol carried out in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="130">The NKÚ-ČR found that it was the transport of taxed products, for which the sender does not need the approval of the tax authority to start.</seg>
<seg id="131">The consignor informed the tax authorities in writing of the start of the transport. The transport was carried out on the basis of accompanying documents, which are used for the transport of products under the conditional exemption scheme;</seg>
<seg id="132">- a total of 94 shipments of mineral oils, Combined Nomenclature code 2710 11 21, were registered in the Slovak Transport Database for a total volume of 173,000 litres carried out by the Czech tax entity between September 2004 and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="133">The NKÚ-ČR found that between May 2004 and June 2005, the tax entity carried out the transport of 102,000 litres of untaxed mineral oils without the appropriate authorisation.</seg>
<seg id="134">The taxpayer was in possession of a special authorisation for the receipt and use of exempt products, under which it could only supply untaxed products to the holder of the same authorisation.</seg>
<seg id="135">He did not notify the customs office in the Czech Republic of the start of the shipments and did not provide a tax guarantee of CZK 1,207,680 for the transported products.</seg>
<seg id="136">Between July 2005 and December 2005, the tax entity delivered 71,000 litres of taxed mineral oils to the territory of SR. Even in these cases, it failed to comply with the legal obligation by not notifying the customs office of the start of the shipments.</seg>
<seg id="137">The consignor in the Czech Republic can start the transport of products put into free circulation in the tax territory of the Czech Republic to another Member State without the consent of the customs office, but he is obliged to inform the customs office in writing before the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="138">A taxpayer purchasing products put into free circulation for tax purposes in another Member State is required to declare the quantity and guarantee the tax before withdrawing them.</seg>
<seg id="139">The goods may be transported only with a simplified accompanying document, the particulars of which are governed by Regulation No 3649 / 92.</seg>
<seg id="140">This Regulation also allows the use of a movement document for transport under suspension of duty, but it must be clearly indicated that it is a "simplified accompanying document for tax control purposes (products subject to excise duty)."</seg>
<seg id="141">The same rules on the transport and acceptance of products put into free circulation for tax purposes in another Member State apply in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="142">In those cases, the tax entities transported the products put into free circulation with an accompanying document for transport under a conditional exemption scheme, the 3rd and 4th copies of which were submitted by the recipient to the tax authorities in SR for verification.</seg>
<seg id="143">The customs authorities in the Slovak Republic registered these shipments in the database of shipments under suspension of tax, as the accompanying documents did not state that it was a simplified accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="144">The SAO SR compared the transport database of the Czech customs administration with the transport database of the Slovak customs administration and found:</seg>
<seg id="145">- in the databases, the quantity of products transported was reported inconsistently, e.g. mineral oil was given in litres, hectolitres or kilograms; alcohol was given in litres or litres of alcohol, making it more difficult to compare the quantity of goods transported;</seg>
<seg id="146">- the quantity of alcohol transported indicated in the invoices did not match the quantity recorded in the databases,</seg>
<seg id="147">- not all related invoices were listed in the databases;</seg>
<seg id="148">- Two shipments of alcohol from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic were registered in the database of the Slovak customs administration in November 2004 for a total volume of 47,237 litres of alcohol, which were not found in the database of the Czech customs administration.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Slovak side handed over copies of the accompanying documents to the Czech side.</seg>
<seg id="150">5. International exchange of information between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="151">Until 30 June 2005, Council Directive 77 / 799 / EEC on mutual assistance between the competent authorities of the Member States in the field of direct taxation, certain excise duties and taxes on insurance premiums laid down the conditions for cooperation between the administrative authorities of the Member States responsible for the administration of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="152">Regulation No 2073 / 2004 entered into force on 1 July 2005, laying down rules and procedures to enable the competent authorities of the Member States of the European Union to cooperate and exchange the information necessary for the correct assessment of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="153">Each Member State shall designate a central liaison office which shall liaise with other Member States in the field of excise administration and shall be responsible for exchanging information on the movement of excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="154">In the Czech Republic, the "Excise Liaison Office" ("ELO ČR") was established at the GŘC to ensure the exchange of information in the field of excise duties between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="155">With effect from 1 May 2004, ELO at the Poprad Customs Office carried out tasks related to the management of systems for the control of the movement of excise goods (SEED, ISA, EWSE) and the exchange of information in the framework of mutual administrative assistance between the Member States of the European Union and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="156">With effect from 1 July 2005, the tasks of ELO are carried out by the ELO department (based in Poprada) of the Excise Duty Department of the Customs Directorate of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "ELO SR").</seg>
<seg id="157">Under Article 3 (3) of Regulation No 2073 / 2004, the central liaison office is responsible, inter alia, for: - the exchange of data held in the SEED electronic register, - the Early Warning System Excise ("EWSE"), - requests for verification of the movement of excise goods sent to or received from other Member States by the Movement Verification System ("ISA").</seg>
<seg id="158">The content, scope and functions of the SEED, EWSE and ISA systems are governed by Articles 22, 23 and 24 of Regulation No 2073 / 2004.</seg>
<seg id="159">Seed - system for the exchange of information on tax entities trading in excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="160">The system is made up of national registers of excise payers and allows tax authorities in the territory of the European Union to determine whether products subject to excise duty are traded by a person authorised to do so.</seg>
<seg id="161">Each national register shall be made available to the competent authorities of the other Member States for excise purposes only.</seg>
<seg id="162">The central liaison office of each Member State shall ensure that persons involved in the movement of excise goods within the territory of the European Union are able to obtain confirmation of the information held in that database.</seg>
<seg id="163">In accordance with Section 41 of Act No 98 / 2004 Z. z., with Section 39 of Act No 104 / 2004 Z. z., with Section 46 of Act No 105 / 2004 Z. z., with Section 40 of Act No 106 / 2004 Z. z., and with Section 39 of Act No 107 / 2004 Z. z. ELO SR maintains an electronic database containing a register of tax warehouse operators, beneficiaries and tax warehouses - the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="164">Customs offices in SR contribute to the SEED database by registering a tax warehouse, a tax warehouse operator or an authorised recipient in the SysNed application software, which is automatically linked to the ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="165">For example, if a new tax warehouse operator, beneficiary or tax warehouse is registered in the SysNed database, the related data will automatically be transferred to the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="166">The SAO SR found that the exchange of SEED databases between the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic and the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic usually took place once a month during the audited period, exceptionally more than once a month.</seg>
<seg id="167">The SR Customs received 22 SEED files and sent 25 SEED files.</seg>
<seg id="168">Data are transferred to the SEED database in the Czech Republic from the national register, which records all persons authorised to handle products subject to excise duty and issued authorisations to handle such products.</seg>
<seg id="169">Individual customs offices in the Czech Republic do not have access to the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="170">Requests from customs offices to provide information from the SEED database of other member countries are only obtained through ELO ČR.</seg>
<seg id="171">EWSE - an early warning system aimed at controlling the transport of excise goods, through which the transport of risky consignments is announced.</seg>
<seg id="172">On the one hand, the transport of certain products subject to excise duty in quantities exceeding the limits set by the European Commission regulation and, on the other hand, the transport, which is assessed as a risk by the tax authorities, is considered to be a risky consignment.</seg>
<seg id="173">The exchange of information takes two forms:</seg>
<seg id="174">- information - to be sent when the limits are exceeded,</seg>
<seg id="175">- a warning message - is sent when the transport of goods is assessed as a risk.</seg>
<seg id="176">When assessing the level of risk of a consignment, ELO SR uses the SEED database to send a warning message, on the basis of which it checks the data contained in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="177">If the data in the SEED database does not match the data in the accompanying document (for example, the registration number of the consignee of the goods or the registered office of the consignee does not match), ELO SR will draw up a warning message, which it will send to the ELO of the Member State of the consignee of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="178">In drawing up the reports, the ELO follows the regulations of the Tax and Customs Commission CED 317 and CED 457, which, among other things, determine the type and quantity of goods in the appropriate units of measurement for the preparation of information and warning reports.</seg>
<seg id="179">During the audited period, ELO SR sent one warning message to ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, information about the start of shipments of products in quantities exceeding the specified limits is generated automatically when entering data from the accompanying document into the database when approving transport.</seg>
<seg id="181">If, on the basis of its own analysis, the tax authority in the Czech Republic assesses the shipment as risky, it will prepare a so-called warning message, which it will send to the relevant Member State via ELO ČR.</seg>
<seg id="182">In 2005, ELO ČR sent two warning messages to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="183">The ISA - the system for controlling the movement of goods - makes it possible, through requests from the ISA, to control individual movements of products subject to excise duty as well as the control of a specified route of transport between the operators mentioned in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="184">The exchange of information is based on a request in which the ELO of the sending country specifies its requirements.</seg>
<seg id="185">The system is used in particular in cases where the consignor receives certified copy No 3 of the accompanying document and requests, for example, a refund of excise duty, and in cases where the information contained in the accompanying document cannot be verified in the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="186">During the audited period, ELO SR sent 33 requests to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.</seg>
<seg id="187">ELO ČR sent ELO SR 25 requests to the ISA.</seg>
<seg id="188">The customs authorities in the Czech Republic most often checked the data contained in the accompanying documents, in particular the quantity of products received or dispatched, or whether the consignor of the products mentioned in the accompanying document is entitled to handle products subject to excise duty, unless this could be verified in the international database SEED.</seg>
<seg id="189">The ISA applications received in both countries were forwarded to the customs authorities responsible for the consignee or consignor of the excise products.</seg>
<seg id="190">The customs authorities examined the requested data and notified the result of the investigation via ELO to the other Member State.</seg>
<seg id="191">6. Summary</seg>
<seg id="192">The cooperation of the NKÚ-ČR and the SAO SR made it possible to compare the basic legislation governing the area of excise duties in both states, the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic for the initiation and termination of the transport of products under the conditional exemption regime between the two states, the registration of these shipments, and to compare the exchange of information between customs authorities in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="193">6.1 Comparison of legislation on excise duties in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic has revealed differences:</seg>
<seg id="194">(A) the procedure followed by tax entities and tax administrations when commencing the transport of products under a conditional exemption scheme.</seg>
<seg id="195">The transport of products under the conditional exemption regime can only be started by a tax entity in the Czech Republic with the approval of the tax authority, which will allow the start of transport on condition that the transported products have been provided with a tax guarantee equal to the amount of tax due to them.</seg>
<seg id="196">The start of the transport of products under the conditional exemption regime in the Slovak Republic is not subject to the authorisation of the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="197">During the audited period, the tax entity was obliged to notify the tax authority of the start of the transport of alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="198">It was able to start the transport of mineral oils, beer and wine without informing the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="199">In 2006, amendments to all laws on excise duties were gradually adopted in the Slovak Republic, according to which the consignor of goods under the conditional exemption procedure is obliged to send a copy of copy No 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office, which has local jurisdiction over the consignor, before the start of transport;</seg>
<seg id="200">(B) within the time limits for dispatch of copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="201">The recipient in the Czech Republic is obliged to send copies 3 and 4 of the accompanying document to the tax authorities for verification no later than the next working day after the end of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="202">Certified copy No 3 must be sent to the consignor no later than the following working day after receiving it from the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="203">The consignee in SR is obliged to send to the consignor of the products copy No 3, certified by the tax authority and the consignee of the products, no later than the 15th day of the month following the month in which he received the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">6.2. Customs authorities in both the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic keep electronic records of shipments of products under the conditional exemption regime.</seg>
<seg id="205">The content and method of keeping this register is not regulated by law in the Czech Republic or in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="206">The customs authorities in both countries record all the data from the accompanying documents on the basis of which the transport is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="207">There is currently no single electronic system for monitoring the movement of goods under suspension of duty between Member States of the European Union, which would allow excise authorities in individual Member States to obtain real-time information on the movement of goods.</seg>
<seg id="208">Decision 1152 / 2003 / EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 foresees the introduction of an electronic system for monitoring movements of products subject to excise duty from 1 July 2009.</seg>
<seg id="209">On the basis of the agreement on cooperation in control activities, the Czech side handed over to the Slovak side a database of shipments of products under the conditional exemption regime started in the Slovak Republic and ended in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="210">The database contained 5,876 items relating to transported mineral oils, ethyl alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="211">The Slovak side handed over to the Czech side a database of shipments of products under the conditional exemption regime started in the Czech Republic and ended in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="212">The database contained 3,319 items relating to transported mineral oils, ethyl alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="213">The Czech side compared the data on shipments listed in the register of shipments started in the Czech Republic with the register of shipments completed in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="214">The Slovak side compared data on shipments of goods under the conditional exemption regime started in the Slovak Republic and ended in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="215">The comparison of data was made more difficult by the fact that the quantity of goods transported was not reported uniformly in the databases.</seg>
<seg id="216">In cases where it was not possible to clearly attribute the data on individual shipments in the two registers, the accompanying documents were checked and no violations of the conditional exemption scheme or cases of tax evasion were found.</seg>
<seg id="217">On the basis of the findings of the parallel checks, it can be concluded that Member States can obtain valuable information from the transport register in order to improve the management of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="218">The establishment of an electronic system for the movement and control of excise goods within the meaning of Decision No 1152 / 2003 / EC of the European Parliament and of the Council will allow for the electronic transmission of the accompanying document and more effective control of movements under suspension of duty within the territory of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="219">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="220">This report was drawn up in Czech, English and Slovak.</seg>
<seg id="221">The report was signed by the Chairman of the Najvyššššie Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_09_11_OCR" genre="news" origlang="en" sysid="OPPO">
<p>
<seg id="1">Administration of Value Added Tax in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of follow-up</seg>
<seg id="3">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are generally a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">It goes without saying, therefore, that Supreme Audit Institutions (SAIs) should focus their attention in this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">An example of this is value added tax (VAT) fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, a loss of EUR 100 billion is estimated each year in the European Union (EU).</seg>
<seg id="8">As early as 2005, the participants of the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">As part of this cooperation, SAIs can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very suitable area for control cooperation, as it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic ("SAO") and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, "BRH") carried out the first parallel audit action in the field of VAT in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is not confined to a single country but is widespread across the EU, close cooperation between SAIs is needed to ensure a comprehensive assessment of the steps being taken to address the problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two SAIs therefore decided to further develop their cooperation in this area and carried out a parallel follow-up.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Control number: (CZ) 09 / 11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration (D) Bilateral audit with the SAO (follow-up)</seg>
<seg id="18">Objective of the inspection:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the audit operation was to examine the procedure of the tax authorities in the administration of VAT, in particular to verify the procedure for dealing with selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as "Germany"), and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of both countries in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit action was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">It was also intended to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control findings were designed to compare with established best practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period covered the years 2006 to 2008 and, in the case of factual links, the periods before and after, until the end of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">A subsequent audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the course of previous parallel checks, suspicious cases of intra-Community transactions were discovered.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them required further examination.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the audit findings, both SAIs formulated recommendations on the management of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up carried out was used to evaluate the measures taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspected cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also focused, for example, on selected cases of high-risk intra-community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of claims and the implementation of VAT controls on large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">When inspecting the VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, the auditors arrived at the following audit findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations from the previous review</seg>
<seg id="33">* Recommendation 1: Conditions for registration of payers should be harmonised across the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel checks, a comparison of VAT registration systems in the two countries revealed differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">As different registration methods cause problems, both SAIs recommended harmonising the conditions for registration of payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation has been presented at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The proposal for an amendment to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218 / 92 ("Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003") called for the extension of existing databases within the EU, including the database of VAT payers' tax identification numbers.</seg>
<seg id="38">It also amended common standards for the registration and deregistration of taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="39">Sai expected EU member states to agree on appropriate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of the document, which was agreed by EU Member States in the framework of ECOFIN, does not contain the issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to see this as a relevant prevention tool in the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">* Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary reports</seg>
<seg id="44">In the framework of international cooperation, a previous control action recommended that all EU countries introduce a one-month deadline for submitting recapitulative statements to allow for a more timely examination of the values of intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common system of value added tax to combat tax evasion linked to intra-Community transactions reduces the reporting period for intra-EU transactions to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1 January 2010, and in Germany it was implemented from 1 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to submit recapitulative statements on a monthly basis was not introduced by the deadline in accordance with the applicable EU rules, while in the Czech Republic it was.</seg>
<seg id="48">* Recommendation 3: Comparing data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in Germany to make VIES data more reliable and considering linking the two systems for VAT returns and recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted the BRH's recommendations and set up a task force to explore possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">Work is still ongoing and the BRH will closely monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">* Recommendation 4: Sharing the successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system at EU level Based on the results of the previous control action, both SAIs agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system need to be exchanged and implemented in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The audit found that our two Member States have different risk management systems, which have their strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the SAO carried out an audit of the EUROCANET system, which allows the exchange of information within the EU, while BRH focused on German participation in the so-called risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Follow-up of selected cases of intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">In the course of the previous control action, commercial transactions where there were doubts about their execution or irregularities in the reporting of commercial transactions in tax returns or recapitulative statements by taxpayers from both countries were jointly examined.</seg>
<seg id="58">Both SAIs selected nine cases for follow-up, which included the intra-community movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="59">The checks carried out by the tax authorities of the respective countries have not been completed by the date of completion of our previous joint control action.</seg>
<seg id="60">The subsequent audit action verified that most of the tax procedures in relation to the selected cases of commercial transactions between payers from the Czech Republic and Germany had been concluded and that adequate measures had been taken by the tax administration of the Czech Republic or Germany (e.g. additional VAT assessments or avoidance of input tax refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Control of selected cases of risky intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">High-risk cases of intra-community transactions carried out by EU payers, which were included in EUROCANET, were selected for inspection.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is a tool for detecting high-risk taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="64">The participation of Member States in this scheme is voluntary.</seg>
<seg id="65">The Czech Republic is an active participant in EUROCANET, while Germany has a passive status.</seg>
<seg id="66">It is unsatisfactory for an active participant in the system if some Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">Due to the fact that the German tax administration was not involved in the exchange of data in EUROCANET, it was not possible to obtain any information on which suppliers with the German VAT ID were assessed as being at risk.</seg>
<seg id="68">As part of the audit operation, the SAO found both cases of normal business transactions and cases with suspicion of involvement in carousel transactions or fraudulent conduct related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tax authorities have limited possibilities to control risky transactions, especially when it comes to so-called missing traders, and it is difficult for a mere physical examination of documents to prove any fraudulent behaviour to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">A similar situation arises for tax administrations when imports and exports to third countries are linked to intra-community carousel trade.</seg>
<seg id="71">In such cases, it would be appropriate to ensure greater cooperation between customs and financial authorities in order to identify goods and inconsistencies in transport documentation, as well as to monitor their physical movement within the EU towards the final consumer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany, like some other countries, is reluctant to actively participate in EUROCANET due to the lack of a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">In Germany, other tools are being used to detect risky taxpayers, which have so far proved successful for the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="74">There is a need for communication and exchange of experience between EU Member States in this area.</seg>
<seg id="75">The EU Council has reached political agreement on a proposal for a Regulation amending Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">Its main innovation is the creation of the EUROFISC network.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far in the use of EUROCANET should be the basis for the creation of this new VAT fraud network.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance for the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">In the area of international debt recovery assistance, all EU Member States are subject to the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, the way in which requests for international assistance for the recovery of claims are handled is the same in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="81">The SAO and BRH compared the statistics submitted by the two Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006-2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">The data contained in these statistics were not consistent.</seg>
<seg id="83">Both SAIs consider it useful to renegotiate the statistics at EU level in order to find a way to avoid persistent mismatches.</seg>
<seg id="84">Without this, the statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the SAIs agree that reliable statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">It would probably be useful for the Commission to carry out an analysis on the basis of more detailed statistics to help Member States strengthen the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">In the view of both SAIs, this means helping Member States with low recovery rates to increase recovery rates to at least the EU average.</seg>
<seg id="88">If a Member State so wishes, the Commission should be actively involved in this process.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. Control of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="90">The Sai analysed the legal situation regarding the VAT control of large tax entities ("VDS") in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they collected information from tax administrations in the form of a questionnaire on areas considered by the SAI to be essential for the management of this issue.</seg>
<seg id="92">It is clear from the responses received that the situation in the two countries is different.</seg>
<seg id="93">The Czech Republic has a system in place to guide the selection of risk-prone cases, which is based on a large amount of relevant data (e.g. information from tax checks carried out, data from balance sheets and profit and loss accounts, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="94">This ensures effective management and analysis of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="95">In 2012, it is planned to set up a specialised financial office for the management of the VDS.</seg>
<seg id="96">A similar system does not yet exist in Germany, which makes it difficult to manage and analyse VAT controls in general.</seg>
<seg id="97">Germany has so far focused more on the selection of the individual cases in question, mainly on the basis of data from VAT returns and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="98">The analysis of these data is based on different components of risk management, which will be strengthened.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Progress of the control action</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Running of the control event in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">The audit was carried out between May 2009 and February 2010 by the Department II - the revenue department of the state budget and the regional unions IX. Plzeň, X. České Budějovice, XIII. Brno and XV. Ostrava.</seg>
