<seg id="517">* Entities linked in chains and networks that are suspected of widespread tax evasion and the unjustified diversion of excess deductions.</seg>
<seg id="518">The number of tax checks carried out by the specialised inspection units of the FO and the results of these checks are shown in Table 3.</seg>
<seg id="519">The Czech Ministry of Finance has proposed an amendment to Act No 531 / 1990 Coll., on Territorial Financial Bodies, which consists of the establishment of a specialised FÚ with a nationwide remit for selected tax entities (including for legal entities established for business purposes, which have achieved a turnover of more than CZK 2 billion).</seg>
<seg id="520">4.5.2 Control of large tax entities in Germany</seg>
<seg id="521">General information</seg>
<seg id="522">VAT controls on large companies are governed by the same rules as tax controls in general, i.e. the relevant provisions are enshrined in the following regulations: The German Fiscal Code (AO), the Fiscal Administration Act (FVG), the Tax Control Regulations (BPO).</seg>
<seg id="523">Other methodological documents are also in force.</seg>
<seg id="524">German Fiscal Code</seg>
<seg id="525">The statutory provisions relating to the inspection are laid down in Articles 193-203 of the German Fiscal Code in Section IV - Tax inspection on the spot. In particular, these articles lay down the rules on the admissibility of tax inspection on the spot (i.e. on the premises of the company), their scope in terms of subject matter, the rules on the allocation of responsibilities, the form and content of the inspection notice, the principles of control, the obligation of the tax entity to cooperate and the preconditions for carrying out the final discussion and communication of the inspection report.</seg>
<seg id="526">On-the-spot tax checks are carried out by the competent tax authorities (Article 195 of the Code).</seg>
<seg id="527">The Fiscal Administration Act According to Article 5.1 (1), in connection with Article 19 of the Act, participation in on-the-spot tax checks carried out by the tax authorities is compulsory for the Federal Central Tax Office.</seg>
<seg id="528">The participating authorities shall agree on the spot on the nature and extent of the participation of the Federal Central Tax Office in the tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="529">In addition, the Federal Central Tax Office has the right to require the specific undertakings it selects to be inspected at a time to be determined by it.</seg>
<seg id="530">In such a case, it may lay down rules on the conduct and content of inspections at the premises of those companies.</seg>
<seg id="531">Rules on tax controls According to Article 108.7 of the German Constitution, the rules on tax controls (German acronym BPO 2000) have been agreed by the Bundesrat, the upper house of the German Parliament, in which the governments of the Länder are represented.</seg>
<seg id="532">These administrative rules apply to on-the-spot checks carried out both by the tax authorities of the Länder and by the Federal Central Tax Office.</seg>
<seg id="533">Undertakings are classified according to size at regular intervals, in accordance with Article 3 of the BPO 2000.</seg>
<seg id="534">Large enterprises are subject to ex post control (Article 4.2 BPO).</seg>
<seg id="535">According to Article 33.1 of the BPO 2000, each informed tax office must keep a register of groups of companies as defined in the BPO 2000.</seg>
<seg id="536">Methodological guidelines</seg>
<seg id="537">In addition to the above, the additional methodology for tax administration is set out in the following guidelines:</seg>
<seg id="538">A single manual for special VAT controls in Germany;</seg>
<seg id="539">The USLO Manual, which sets out the methodology for the use of data on intra-community trade relations conducted in VIES;</seg>
<seg id="540">The Zauber Manual, which sets out the methodology for the use of the Zauber database;</seg>
<seg id="541">Work aids for various and special items.</seg>
<seg id="542">The classification of tax entities is based on criteria such as turnover and net profit, with different limits depending on the type of business.</seg>
<seg id="543">The data are published by the Federal Ministry of Finance.</seg>
<seg id="544">They are evaluated every three years and fixed for the next three years.</seg>
<seg id="545">The number of companies to be inspected - not just large companies - must be determined at regular intervals.</seg>
<seg id="546">As a general rule, checks on large enterprises are carried out on an ongoing basis.</seg>
<seg id="547">Checks are usually announced, including VAT checks.</seg>
<seg id="548">This means that, in the course of the inspection, checks will be carried out definitively, mainly on income tax, excise duty and VAT - i.e. checks on all types of relevant taxes.</seg>
<seg id="549">VAT checks may be carried out either by tax inspectors or by VAT inspectors.</seg>
<seg id="550">Implementation varies and depends on the organisation of the Länder.</seg>
<seg id="551">The number of tax years covered by the checks is usually between three and five years.</seg>
<seg id="552">BPO 2000 foresees an inspection period of three years.</seg>
<seg id="553">All taxes of the company are subject to verification.</seg>
<seg id="554">4.5.3 Management of control of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="555">Both SAIs decided not to investigate individual cases of VDS checks carried out, but focused on management issues in order to gain an overview of how tax administrations manage the issue of VAT checks on VDS.</seg>
<seg id="556">In the form of a questionnaire, they collected information from tax administrations on areas they consider essential for managing the issue.</seg>
<seg id="557">* What statistical records and analyses are available to the management of tax administrations regarding the VAT control of the VDS?</seg>
<seg id="558">In particular:</seg>
<seg id="559">Are there any statistics or records of the extent to which a distinction is made between the fight against VAT fraud and VAT control in general?</seg>
<seg id="560">Czech Republic: No, the ADIS system does not allow such a resolution in the current data version.</seg>
<seg id="561">Germany: The tax administration makes no distinction between the control proposed to combat VAT fraud and the general control of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="562">Are there any statistics or records on the timeliness of VAT checks (linked to the time period of the transactions checked)?</seg>
<seg id="563">Czech Republic: Records on the timeliness of enquiries relevant to intra-Community purchases of goods for selected VAT payers are reported in the ADIS system.</seg>
<seg id="564">In addition, the information recorded in ADIS also includes data such as how long the interview took.</seg>
<seg id="565">Germany: No, the uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors contain only information on the average time of the last inspection (information on the year).</seg>
<seg id="566">This figure does not provide an overview of the selected control periods with regard to individual entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="567">VAT inspectors focus on the most recent tax assessment period; they also have the right to carry out VDS checks.</seg>
<seg id="568">However, the statistics produced at the federal level for the special VAT inspection services do not provide information on the classification of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="569">There are some statistics or records on the nature of the additional tax revenue generated, broken down for example according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="570">I. a net increase in the tax liability (e.g. in cases where the taxpayer has improperly applied a reduced VAT rate instead of the standard tax rate);</seg>
<seg id="571">II. only a nominal increase in the tax liability (e.g. transfer of a fully qualified VAT case to another tax year);</seg>
<seg id="572">III. post-clearance recovery of tax revenue (payment of additional tax due).</seg>
<seg id="573">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="574">The Czech tax administration monitors the number of tax verifications carried out, the amounts of additional tax assessed, broken down by type of tax, the number of tax entities audited and the number of tax years audited.</seg>
<seg id="575">Other tax procedures (local investigations, complaints) are followed in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="576">The time data and amounts of additional taxes paid are recorded as a separate task.</seg>
<seg id="577">General debt statistics shall also be kept, broken down by type of tax but not by the declared tax or the tax established by the tax authority.</seg>
<seg id="578">Germany: No, the uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and for the special VAT inspection services do not distinguish between the above criteria.</seg>
<seg id="579">In addition, the majority of tax administrations visited do not distinguish between these differences.</seg>
<seg id="580">Are there areas of control that generate significant additional revenue?</seg>
<seg id="581">Czech Republic: Yes, the tax authority has the right to collect the tax payer for verification on the basis of criteria that can be linked to selected indicators in the special sections of ADIS.</seg>
<seg id="582">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="583">It follows that uniform statistics at federal level do not provide such data for tax inspectors and for the special VAT inspection services.</seg>
<seg id="584">However, there is one coordinated approach between the finance ministers of the Länder and the federal government.</seg>
<seg id="585">In the Zauber database, tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder are required to record the increased tax (VAT) liability they have assessed if they exceed a certain amount.</seg>
<seg id="586">In such a case, it must specify, for example, the nature of the increase in the tax liability assessed.</seg>
<seg id="587">What are the most common findings?</seg>
<seg id="588">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="589">- VDCs exercise an unjustified right to deduct input tax on supplies and services:</seg>
<seg id="590">(A) which have not been used to carry out any economic activity pursuant to Section 72 (1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="591">(A) which have been used for representation under Section 75 (3) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="592">On the basis of tax documents which did not meet the requirements set out in Section 73 (1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="593">- VDS did not declare output VAT pursuant to Section 21 (1) of the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: It has been noted that there are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">It follows that uniform statistics at federal level do not provide such data for tax inspectors and for the special VAT inspection services.</seg>
<seg id="596">VAT findings are not separately registered by the Länder if they result from VDS tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, in the Zauber database, where tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder are required to record the increased tax (VAT) liability they have assessed if they exceed a certain amount, the Federal Central Tax Office is able to analyse this information.</seg>
<seg id="598">Does the tax administration carry out analyses of areas of control that generate a high "return" and draw conclusions for management?</seg>
<seg id="599">Czech Republic: Yes, for example, they are launching national audits focused on risky commodities or on the subject of economic activity.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">Uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and for special VAT inspection services do not provide data on audit areas that generate high "revenue."</seg>
<seg id="602">There are different views on the process of analysis, as well as on case management in terms of relevance.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some regional tax authorities provide special information, but its use is at the discretion of the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">The differences in the replies of the two Member States show that the Czech Republic provides a system that collects a number of data from the tax checks carried out, as well as data from the financial statements - balance sheet and profit and loss accounts.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to guide the selection of risk-prone cases.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the analysis and management of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, the establishment of a specialised financial office for the management of the VDS is planned in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax authorities do not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">It follows that it is more difficult to carry out those tasks in a similar manner.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, Germany's philosophy puts more emphasis on selecting individual cases based on data from submitted tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="612">Therefore, the risk management components will be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of adequate reference notes, expert auditors must be able to assess the exact amount of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="614">Both SAIs agree that Member States should be able to ensure adequate financial management as well as an adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help to reduce shortfalls in VAT revenue.</seg>
<seg id="616">As a result, the revenue from VAT collection will be increased and the level of risk detection for unreliable entrepreneurs will be improved.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation of the two SAIs on parallel audits of the VAT administration met the objectives set by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">The two SAIs got to know each other better about the systems in place in the following areas: (I) intra-community transactions, (ii) VAT risk management, in particular as regards the collection of risk-prone transactions, (iii) VAT recovery assistance and (iii) VAT control of large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to mutual cooperation, differences in VAT fraud detection strategies as well as differences in the above-mentioned areas of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany have been revealed.</seg>
<seg id="621">The control findings were compared and best practices were identified.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, both SAIs hope that the results achieved will provide an impetus for stakeholders to start a discussion on approaches and strategies within Member States, including at European Commission level.</seg>
<seg id="623">The extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation between the two SAIs can serve as an encouragement for the implementation of future control actions in the field of VAT management.</seg>
